WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:01.340
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnett:
Hello, everyone.

00:00:01.340 --> 00:00:06.180
Welcome to the Graphic
Novels Program.

00:00:06.180 --> 00:00:08.840
My name is Sarah Burnett,
and I serve as the director

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:11.430
of operations for
the Small Press Expo.

00:00:11.430 --> 00:00:12.900
Our executive director,
Warren Bernard,

00:00:12.900 --> 00:00:14.200
was supposed to be here.

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:16.250
He sends his regrets and
requests for painkillers

00:00:16.250 --> 00:00:18.180
because he pulled his back out.

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:21.040
I'm so pleased that I
can stand in for him.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:23.710
I've got to tell you, it's
tough to reconcile being someone

00:00:23.710 --> 00:00:26.030
who usually spends a
Saturday afternoon curled

00:00:26.030 --> 00:00:29.220
up with a book standing in
front of a large crowd, [laughs]

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:31.100
but I get the sense that
you guys are my people,

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:33.700
and I'm really glad
we're all here today.

00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:36.600
The Small Press Expo,
or SPX, has been proud

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:39.790
to help organize the lineup
of graphic novel authors here

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:43.310
at the National Book
Festival for the last 5 years.

00:00:43.310 --> 00:00:46.300
This year, we're particularly
excited to support appearances

00:00:46.300 --> 00:00:48.820
by Tillie Walden
and Ed Piskor today.

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:51.870
Both have been mainstays at SPX.

00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:54.210
Our show this year
is just 2 weeks away

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:55.610
and will feature many authors

00:00:55.610 --> 00:00:58.050
and artists you're familiar
with, like Roz Chast,

00:00:58.050 --> 00:01:01.210
Jules Feiffer, Derf
Backderf, and Carol Tyler.

00:01:01.210 --> 00:01:03.450
We'll also have folks
like Rebecca Sugar

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:06.970
of Steven Universe
fame and Ngozi Ukazu,

00:01:06.970 --> 00:01:08.820
whose web comic Check, Please!

00:01:08.820 --> 00:01:12.430
became the most funded web
comic kickstarter of all time.

00:01:12.430 --> 00:01:15.150
With more than 600 creators
on our exhibiter list,

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:17.480
you'll discover a lot
of new talent too.

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:20.070
I hope you'll join us
just outside the city

00:01:20.070 --> 00:01:22.130
at the Bethesda North
Marriott Conference Center

00:01:22.130 --> 00:01:24.300
on September 15th and 16th

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:26.810
so we can continue celebrating
great authors and artists

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:28.780
like the ones you're
about to get to know.

00:01:28.780 --> 00:01:31.620
There are some flyers that can
you grab at the back of the room

00:01:31.620 --> 00:01:34.380
to learn more, and hope
you plan to join us.

00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:36.740
Now, for why you're really
here, it is my pleasure

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:38.580
to introduce Michael Cavna.

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:40.620
Michael is the columnist
and cartoonist

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:42.290
with The Washington Post.

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:44.950
His prose and pictures for
The Post have been honored

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:47.400
by the Society of
Professional Journalists,

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:50.950
National Headliner Awards, the
Society for Feature Journalists,

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:53.530
the Harvey Awards,
and the Eisner Awards.

00:01:53.530 --> 00:01:57.510
This is Michael's fifth year as
the founding emcee and moderator

00:01:57.510 --> 00:02:00.370
of the festival's graphic
novel stage programming.

00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:04.060
Please join me and welcome
him, and let's get started.

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:06.110
[ Applause ]

00:02:06.110 --> 00:02:08.410
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Thank you, Sarah.

00:02:09.770 --> 00:02:11.540
Thank you guys for coming out.

00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:15.070
Are you ready for
2 hours of comics?

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:17.670
This is the recess
of the festival.

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:19.680
This is when you were in school.

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:23.080
You know, we can bring my
Post colleague David Ignatius,

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:24.380
you know.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:27.300
He's our social studies
class, and all, and I sat next

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:29.300
to Jon Meacham last
night and was talking

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:32.470
about presidential history,
and he was reassuring me

00:02:32.470 --> 00:02:35.940
that 1933 wasn't so
different from this year.

00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:39.650
And then, we had a few
drinks or a lot of drinks.

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:42.400
And I mentioned drinks
because this was started based

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:43.700
on drinks.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:46.460
It's adult recess.

00:02:46.460 --> 00:02:50.910
This festival started, you
know, by Laura Bush was

00:02:50.910 --> 00:02:53.160
who really got it
going, backed it.

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:55.710
But for years, there
was no separate graphic

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:57.010
novels programming.

00:02:57.010 --> 00:02:58.430
They were individual stages.

00:02:58.430 --> 00:03:00.240
And then, you had some
enlightened people talk

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:03.330
to the Library of Congress,
took them out for beers,

00:03:03.330 --> 00:03:06.280
got them a little drunk,
and said, you need comics.

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:07.830
This is our fifth
year doing this,

00:03:07.830 --> 00:03:10.590
so for the grown-ups,
alcohol can work.

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:14.640
Again, my name's Michael
Cavna of The Washington Post.

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:17.670
The Washington Post is a charter
sponsor of this festival.

00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:21.090
I do want to give a big
shout out and thank you

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:24.240
to the festival co-chairman,
David Rubenstein,

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:27.630
and all the generous sponsors
who make this event possible.

00:03:27.630 --> 00:03:28.930
It's huge.

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:30.230
And if you, per chance,

00:03:30.230 --> 00:03:32.620
would like to add your
financial support,

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:33.920
you know, please feel free.

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:36.400
There's information in your
program about how to do that.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:38.790
And at the end of the
2-hour, near the end

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:42.360
of the 2-hour presentation, we
should have time for questions.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:46.450
We will have monitors, I
mean, microphones right there.

00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:51.830
And just for everyone, the,
this is being videotaped,

00:03:51.830 --> 00:03:54.640
so if you do appear, do come
to a microphone, you may show

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:57.100
up in a broadcast or
in some other way.

00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:59.210
So you're agreeing.

00:03:59.210 --> 00:04:03.700
That's your consent if
you dare walk up here.

00:04:03.700 --> 00:04:05.420
The, one thing David
Rubenstein didn't talk

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:08.840
about last night was
literacy, the high degree

00:04:08.840 --> 00:04:11.380
of illiteracy in this country.

00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:14.490
Also, just being a
reluctant reader.

00:04:14.490 --> 00:04:16.860
We often get teachers
here, and for comics,

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:19.560
it's very much the
power of comics is

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:23.170
to activate your brain
in different areas.

00:04:23.170 --> 00:04:24.590
Some of us are visual learners.

00:04:24.590 --> 00:04:26.780
Some of us, it triggers,
you know.

00:04:26.780 --> 00:04:29.700
I've talked to students
who it gets things going.

00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:32.930
So a big reason we do this
is because graphic novels

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:36.030
and comics are huge to
get young people to read.

00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:40.350
So we have several Eisner
winner awards tonight.

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:43.920
We have a big Reuben
Award winner to my right.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:46.990
And his name is Mr. Patrick
McDonnell, the creator of Mutts.

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:49.010
Can I get a big hand
for Patrick McDonnell?

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:50.410
[ Applause ]

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:52.210
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Thank you.

00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:57.260
[ Applause ]

00:04:57.260 --> 00:05:00.080
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Mutts, as you
may know, was started in 1994.

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:03.050
It's in more than 700
papers, last I looked.

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:06.030
You may have picked up
some since we sat down.

00:05:06.030 --> 00:05:07.910
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Nowadays, it's a little tough

00:05:07.910 --> 00:05:09.210
to pick up newspapers.

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:10.510
[laughter]

00:05:10.510 --> 00:05:13.220
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: But as you
know, Mutts is the lovable,

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:18.170
sort of New Jersey world of Earl
and Mooch, the dog and the cat.

00:05:18.170 --> 00:05:23.940
Just as a baseline, do we have
any fans of cats or dogs here?

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:26.800
Really? Not so good.

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:28.100
All right.

00:05:28.100 --> 00:05:30.320
I won't separate and say which
is the better animal to own,

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:34.850
but, you know, and you have
is the, it's a strip that is,

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:39.840
it's special, and it's both, it
makes you feel good to read it,

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:43.760
but it's also artistically
the epitome of the art form.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:46.020
Charles Schulz, who
we both would meet

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:50.060
at National Cartooning Society
conventions, he called Mutts --

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:51.690
and as you know, he was
the creator of Peanuts --

00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:54.880
he called Mutts one of the
best comic strips of all time.

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:58.560
He said, "Mutts is exactly
what a comic strip should be."

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:00.880
And Matt Groening, the
creator of The Simpsons, said,

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:02.960
"Mutts cheers me up every day."

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:05.230
And I don't know about you,
but some days, these days,

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:08.080
I need a little cheering
up in my morning newspaper.

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:10.070
And so I turn to Mutts.

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:12.610
It's just, it's a
tremendous feat,

00:06:12.610 --> 00:06:14.560
but he's also a children's
illustrator.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.200
He's also a playwright.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:19.490
Mutts has spawned 3 books
-- I mean, many books,

00:06:19.490 --> 00:06:21.800
dozens of books --
but such books is Year

00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:25.280
of Yesh is what it
is, and #ILoveMutts

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:27.200
and The Mutts Spring Diaries.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:32.160
He's really the man who taught
us how to say "yesh" with an H

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:36.200
and "snax" with an X. And
his play, The, his book,

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:39.000
The Gift of Nothing, was
adapted into a play that played

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.080
at the Kennedy Center that
won Helen Hayes Awards.

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:43.960
He also did the book, Me...

00:06:43.960 --> 00:06:48.990
Jane, with, about Jane Goodall,
and that won a Caldecott Award.

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:50.380
So basically, you're
just hitting

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:52.340
on all cylinders these days.

00:06:52.340 --> 00:06:53.640
So 1 more hand.

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.610
He's doing it all for
everything he does.

00:06:56.610 --> 00:06:58.510
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Thank you.

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:01.150
[ Applause ]

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:02.450
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So am I right?

00:07:02.450 --> 00:07:03.750
Am I forgetting?

00:07:03.750 --> 00:07:05.050
Is Mutts, will Mutts
be a feature film?

00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:06.350
Is that going to happen?

00:07:06.350 --> 00:07:07.650
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Knock on wood, someday.

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:08.950
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

00:07:08.950 --> 00:07:10.250
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Hollywood works a little slower

00:07:10.250 --> 00:07:11.550
than daily comic strips.

00:07:11.550 --> 00:07:12.850
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

00:07:12.850 --> 00:07:14.150
Well, let's get to
our images, and --

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:15.680
oh, good, we do have
the cover there.

00:07:15.680 --> 00:07:16.980
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Oh, good.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:18.280
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Good to see it, yeah.

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:19.880
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Well, you
know, I, much as my combination

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:23.670
of my love for the art of
comics and my love for animals,

00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:28.020
so I brought slides that
show my love for comics

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:29.320
and my love for animals.

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:30.620
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:31.920
Now, you are an illustrator.

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:33.220
You were doing things
for the New York Times

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:35.520
and many other publications
before you launched Mutts.

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:37.820
Were -- I know I've
talked to other creators

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:41.050
who do [inaudible] animals, and
the animals were often popping

00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:43.980
up in their margins or animal
characters would just keep

00:07:43.980 --> 00:07:45.750
speaking to them
when they would draw.

00:07:45.750 --> 00:07:48.310
When did animals sort
of enter your page?

00:07:48.310 --> 00:07:49.610
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
That's funny.

00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:50.910
I always wanted to be
a comic strip artist,

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:52.210
but when I graduated
from school,

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:54.030
I started getting
magazine illustration work,

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:58.090
and that kept me busy
for quite a few years.

00:07:58.090 --> 00:07:59.630
But in my magazine
illustrations,

00:07:59.630 --> 00:08:01.610
I always drew a little,
white dog with a circle

00:08:01.610 --> 00:08:04.580
around his eye just in
the background somewhere.

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:06.590
And I didn't have a
dog at that point,

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:07.900
but I really wanted a dog.

00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:09.200
And he didn't have a name.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:10.500
He was just this random dog.

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:13.660
But when I finally decided I
wanted to do a comic strip,

00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:17.000
I actually went out and
got a Jack Russell Terrier,

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:18.300
and his name was Earl.

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:19.600
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:20.900
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: And
he inspired the comic.

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:24.710
So the illustrated, the cartoon
dog I was drawing became a real

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:26.890
dog, and then the real
dog became the cartoon.

00:08:26.890 --> 00:08:28.190
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

00:08:28.190 --> 00:08:31.380
And did that real dog demand
royalties from the other dog?

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:33.750
[ Laughter ]

00:08:33.750 --> 00:08:37.160
But, you know, we're going to
concentrate on a couple themes

00:08:37.160 --> 00:08:41.000
that consistently come up
in Mutts, and one of those,

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.030
we spoke of Charles Schulz.

00:08:43.030 --> 00:08:45.770
And, you know, there
is a through line.

00:08:45.770 --> 00:08:49.530
I mean, the fact that Sparky
is, as we call him, you know,

00:08:49.530 --> 00:08:51.160
he personally blessed your --

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:53.070
he, Sparky didn't
like everything,

00:08:53.070 --> 00:08:55.410
and he would let you know
it, but he loved Mutts.

00:08:55.410 --> 00:08:57.550
So can you talk about
what you're doing here?

00:08:57.550 --> 00:08:58.850
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Well,
I'll read the strip real quick.

00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:00.150
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:01.450
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Charles Schulz said,

00:09:01.450 --> 00:09:02.750
"A cartoonist is someone who
has to draw the same thing day

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:04.740
after day without
repeating himself."

00:09:04.740 --> 00:09:07.360
Yesh, you can say that again.

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:09.580
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: [laughs]
And then, we have a follow-up.

00:09:09.580 --> 00:09:10.880
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Charles Schulz said,

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:12.700
"A cartoonist is someone who
has to draw the same thing day

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:15.300
after day without
repeating himself."

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:16.600
He said what?

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:17.900
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Oh, man.

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:19.410
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: I
literally did that for a week.

00:09:19.410 --> 00:09:21.080
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow, yeah.

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:22.520
You literally repeated yourself.

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:24.090
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: And
then, I enjoyed it so much,

00:09:24.090 --> 00:09:26.310
a couple of months
later, I did a few more.

00:09:26.310 --> 00:09:28.370
[laughter] And I think
I might've used it

00:09:28.370 --> 00:09:29.670
as much as I can.

00:09:29.670 --> 00:09:31.600
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay, so this
isn't appearing next week as a--

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:32.900
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: It might.

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:34.200
[laughter]

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:35.500
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And so--

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:36.800
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: It's
actually a great quote,

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:38.650
and Charles Schulz is the
reason I became a cartoonist.

00:09:38.650 --> 00:09:40.070
I mean, I grew up with Peanuts.

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:43.810
And the fact that I actually got
to become friends with my hero

00:09:43.810 --> 00:09:46.060
and idol was just amazing.

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:47.650
And when he said he
liked Mutts, I said,

00:09:47.650 --> 00:09:48.950
okay, I could retire now.

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:50.250
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Right?

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:51.550
Yeah, exactly.

00:09:51.550 --> 00:09:52.850
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Instead, I kept on doing it.

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:54.550
And actually, next year's
going to be 25 years of Mutts.

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:56.000
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Wow, congratulations.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.880
That's a huge, [applause] in
this market and everything.

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:01.690
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Well, you
know, when you think about it,

00:10:01.690 --> 00:10:02.990
Charles Schulz did
it for 50 years.

00:10:02.990 --> 00:10:04.290
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Fifty years.

00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:05.590
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
I'm only halfway there.

00:10:05.590 --> 00:10:06.890
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Really, so
you're going to keep -- okay.

00:10:06.890 --> 00:10:08.190
You're going to repeat
yourself for 50 years.

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:09.490
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: I'm
not going to promise that.

00:10:09.490 --> 00:10:10.790
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay, but,

00:10:10.790 --> 00:10:12.210
so to continue the
theme of the meta here.

00:10:12.210 --> 00:10:13.510
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Yeah, so,

00:10:13.510 --> 00:10:15.200
do you have any ideas
for today's comic?

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:16.500
No, but I'm sure I'm come

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:18.530
up with something
by the third panel.

00:10:18.530 --> 00:10:20.270
Boy, that got here fast.

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:22.110
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Now, is that
how you feel as an artist?

00:10:22.110 --> 00:10:24.490
You know, some, like,
prefer the 4-panel thing?

00:10:24.490 --> 00:10:26.800
They like a longer arc
to build to the joke.

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:30.640
But some, you know,
you're, you, 3 panels seem

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:31.940
to be your main thing.

00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:33.240
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Yeah,
most of my strips are 3 panels.

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:35.060
It's really, it's the
classic way to tell a story.

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:38.370
It's the setup, and then,
you know, the action,

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:39.940
and then the punchline.

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:41.240
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:10:41.240 --> 00:10:42.540
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
So 3 panels work,

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:44.620
but they do come fast sometimes.

00:10:44.620 --> 00:10:45.920
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:47.260
[laughter] Well,
continue, again, the meta.

00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:48.560
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Okay.

00:10:48.560 --> 00:10:50.460
Cat Comics by Mooch.

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:54.260
I'm thinking of sch-making
this into a graphic novel.

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.030
[laughter] I bought this
one because I was surprised

00:10:56.030 --> 00:10:58.280
when I was asked to be on
the graphic novels panel.

00:10:58.280 --> 00:11:00.630
I don't, you know, I'm
doing a graphic novel,

00:11:00.630 --> 00:11:02.920
but it's taken 24
years to write.

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:07.630
And I feel like Mooch would,
if a cat did a graphic novel,

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:11.910
just different favorite naps
would be a good graphic novel.

00:11:11.910 --> 00:11:16.570
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And when, you
know, the animal [inaudible] is

00:11:16.570 --> 00:11:18.320
such a distinctive part.

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:21.130
No one does it like that now.

00:11:21.130 --> 00:11:23.830
Did that, was that organic
from the beginning, or--

00:11:23.830 --> 00:11:25.130
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Well, you know, I was,

00:11:25.130 --> 00:11:27.180
I'm a big fan of
old comic strips.

00:11:27.180 --> 00:11:29.460
And old comic strips,
people used to have little,

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:30.760
silly ways of talking.

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:32.680
I mean, Popeye says,
"I yam what I yam."

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:33.980
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:35.280
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
And Barney Google.

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:37.220
You know, every, there was more
of like playing with language,

00:11:37.220 --> 00:11:38.520
so I thought one

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:39.820
of my characters should
talk a little silly.

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:42.710
And when Mooch came up, I
thought he was the character

00:11:42.710 --> 00:11:44.100
that should talk a little silly.

00:11:44.100 --> 00:11:47.490
And I had a friend growing up
who, whenever he got in trouble

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:50.090
and had to admit to
something, he would say, yesh.

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:53.140
And I thought "yesh" would be
a funny thing for Mooch to say.

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:55.030
And then, I had him
say "sch-maybe,"

00:11:55.030 --> 00:11:56.330
and then it just got
out of hand, and--

00:11:56.330 --> 00:11:57.630
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: There you go.

00:11:57.630 --> 00:11:58.930
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: He's
shushing all over the place.

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:01.120
I literally once had a woman
write me a 2-page letter

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:05.060
that said she was really upset
that Mooch talked like that.

00:12:05.060 --> 00:12:06.360
And at the end of the letter,

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:09.950
her thesis was her cat
would never talk like that.

00:12:09.950 --> 00:12:12.090
[laughter] I wrote her
a little note back,

00:12:12.090 --> 00:12:13.390
and I just wrote, "Sch-orry."

00:12:13.390 --> 00:12:14.690
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:15.990
[laughter] Nice.

00:12:15.990 --> 00:12:17.660
I thought you were going
to call the authority-sch,

00:12:17.660 --> 00:12:19.590
maybe, on that.

00:12:19.590 --> 00:12:21.360
Do your characters speak to you?

00:12:21.360 --> 00:12:23.770
Some creators have told me
they know they're in the zone

00:12:23.770 --> 00:12:26.880
when their creators, when their
characters are practically

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:28.180
speaking to them.

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:29.480
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Yeah,
well, you know, I mean,

00:12:29.480 --> 00:12:31.070
it's a corny thing to say,
but the characters come,

00:12:31.070 --> 00:12:33.030
sometimes do write themselves.

00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:37.340
The way I'm work, I'm visual,
so my notebooks isn't, you know,

00:12:37.340 --> 00:12:39.090
writing as much as drawing.

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:40.470
So I'll just draw
Mooch, and I'll think,

00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:41.770
well, what could he do?

00:12:41.770 --> 00:12:43.070
And put him in a
certain situation.

00:12:43.070 --> 00:12:44.830
And then, he kind of
takes over and tells me--

00:12:44.830 --> 00:12:46.130
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: There he goes.

00:12:46.130 --> 00:12:47.430
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Tells me what to draw.

00:12:47.430 --> 00:12:48.730
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: There he goes.

00:12:48.730 --> 00:12:50.030
Okay.

00:12:50.030 --> 00:12:51.330
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Like this one.

00:12:51.330 --> 00:12:52.630
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:53.930
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Think of a punch line.

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:55.230
Oof.

00:12:55.230 --> 00:12:56.530
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: [laughs]
And in a similar vein.

00:12:56.530 --> 00:12:57.830
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Yeah,
again, I've said, well,

00:12:57.830 --> 00:12:59.130
I've brought all the strips
that talk about it too.

00:12:59.130 --> 00:13:00.430
Art of comics.

00:13:00.430 --> 00:13:01.730
So Mooch, in the
first panel, as,

00:13:01.730 --> 00:13:03.030
he's a wizard here,
Prospero [phonetic].

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:06.040
"I will now cast a sch-pell
for us to travel back in time."

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:07.340
Poof. "Wow."

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:11.140
"I will now cast a sch-pell
for us to travel back in time."

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:13.590
So it's, what's kind of
interesting about this strip,

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:16.240
you know, we learn
to read comics.

00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:18.310
It's a very strange
thing, but, you know,

00:13:18.310 --> 00:13:20.840
each panel's a different moment
in time, and it's something

00:13:20.840 --> 00:13:23.230
that you have to
acquire after a while.

00:13:23.230 --> 00:13:26.820
I had a woman that I met
who never read comics,

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:28.120
so she couldn't,
in the beginning,

00:13:28.120 --> 00:13:31.190
she really couldn't figure
out what was going on, but,

00:13:31.190 --> 00:13:34.050
so it's something I think we
just learn, but it was fun

00:13:34.050 --> 00:13:37.890
to play with the concept
of time in a comic strip.

00:13:37.890 --> 00:13:40.260
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And this
is, I was reading something

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:43.210
about the comic Norm Macdonald
the other day talking a platonic

00:13:43.210 --> 00:13:44.510
joke would be where the setup

00:13:44.510 --> 00:13:46.230
and the joke are
almost identical.

00:13:46.230 --> 00:13:48.510
Well, if you were an anime,
if you were a manga reader,

00:13:48.510 --> 00:13:50.200
you could read this
right to left,

00:13:50.200 --> 00:13:52.110
and it would work just as well.

00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:55.810
[laughter] It would literally,
it's that circle, you know.

00:13:55.810 --> 00:13:58.170
It's a platonic strip.

00:13:58.170 --> 00:14:01.980
Sparky really knew what the heck
he was talking about, basically.

00:14:01.980 --> 00:14:03.280
And so more fun.

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:04.580
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: So
here's Prospero again.

00:14:04.580 --> 00:14:06.480
"As the great cat wizard,
I can see into the future.

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:07.780
How does it look?

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:09.080
Empty for now."

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:10.380
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And then,

00:14:10.380 --> 00:14:11.680
what other art form
could you do this?

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:15.070
Play with the art form within
the art form in this way.

00:14:15.070 --> 00:14:16.370
Oh, I love this.

00:14:16.370 --> 00:14:17.670
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Oh, here's one.

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:18.970
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:14:18.970 --> 00:14:20.270
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: And
this one isn't going to appear

00:14:20.270 --> 00:14:21.570
until next Sunday,
so you're getting a--

00:14:21.570 --> 00:14:22.870
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: A tease.

00:14:22.870 --> 00:14:24.170
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
A tease here.

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:25.470
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: All right.

00:14:25.470 --> 00:14:26.770
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: "Va-voom."

00:14:26.770 --> 00:14:28.070
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Are they
allowed to take pictures

00:14:28.070 --> 00:14:29.370
and post on social media?

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:30.670
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: No, don't.

00:14:30.670 --> 00:14:31.970
[laughs] "Va-voom."

00:14:31.970 --> 00:14:33.270
"What was that?"

00:14:33.270 --> 00:14:34.570
"Onomatopoeia."

00:14:34.570 --> 00:14:35.870
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Love that.

00:14:35.870 --> 00:14:37.170
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: I've
been doing much for 24 years,

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:38.470
and it's the first time
onomatopoeia was a punch line.

00:14:38.470 --> 00:14:39.770
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

00:14:39.770 --> 00:14:41.070
And you're going to
teach a few people too.

00:14:41.070 --> 00:14:42.370
They will, the Google,
there will be a Google spike

00:14:42.370 --> 00:14:43.670
for that on Sunday morning.

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:44.990
So another key theme
and huge part

00:14:44.990 --> 00:14:48.630
of Mutts is not only the
laughter, but the heart,

00:14:48.630 --> 00:14:53.920
the soul, and you, you know,
you have this uncanny ability

00:14:53.920 --> 00:14:57.320
in 5 panels or 3
to also just yank

00:14:57.320 --> 00:14:58.700
on our heartstrings so hard.

00:14:58.700 --> 00:15:00.000
It's a gift.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.300
It's, you know, you
really do it.

00:15:01.300 --> 00:15:05.870
And can you talk a little bit
about just the origin of this

00:15:05.870 --> 00:15:08.390
and the response you get
from doing Shelter Stories?

00:15:08.390 --> 00:15:09.690
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
I'll read this one first.

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:10.990
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:15:10.990 --> 00:15:12.290
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: So this
is Shelter Stories, Bowser.

00:15:12.290 --> 00:15:13.590
"I was the first
picked from my litter.

00:15:13.590 --> 00:15:15.790
My family thought I was
the cutest little thing.

00:15:15.790 --> 00:15:17.090
In a year, I was gone.

00:15:17.090 --> 00:15:18.920
It was a matter of size.

00:15:18.920 --> 00:15:21.210
I got big, and their
hearts got small."

00:15:21.210 --> 00:15:22.510
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Oh.

00:15:22.510 --> 00:15:23.810
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Yeah.

00:15:23.810 --> 00:15:25.110
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Oh, man.

00:15:25.110 --> 00:15:26.410
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: You
know, I was doing mutts

00:15:26.410 --> 00:15:30.370
for about 4 years and, or maybe
3 and a half, and I was thinking

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:33.400
that Earl and Mooch have loving
guardians and a loving home,

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:35.890
but I was thinking about all
the dogs and cats in shelters

00:15:35.890 --> 00:15:37.620
that are waiting for
that opportunity.

00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:40.390
And I was trying to, I was in my
sketchbook trying to figure out,

00:15:40.390 --> 00:15:43.220
how can I get shelter
animals into the Mutts world?

00:15:43.220 --> 00:15:45.160
And then, a woman from
the Humane Society

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:46.740
of the United States
wrote to me and said

00:15:46.740 --> 00:15:50.450
that November's National Animal
Shelter Appreciation Week,

00:15:50.450 --> 00:15:51.750
Month.

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:53.060
And could I do something?

00:15:53.060 --> 00:15:55.080
I said, well, that's
the perfect opportunity.

00:15:55.080 --> 00:15:58.390
So I started Shelter Stories,
which I do twice a year --

00:15:58.390 --> 00:16:01.370
one, the first week in May and
the first week in November.

00:16:01.370 --> 00:16:03.310
They just remind the readers
that if they're thinking

00:16:03.310 --> 00:16:05.200
about getting a new best friend,

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:06.890
that the shelter
was the place to go.

00:16:06.890 --> 00:16:08.190
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
So you're funny,

00:16:08.190 --> 00:16:09.540
but you're saving
lives, to be honest.

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:10.840
[laughs] You're literally,

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:12.500
you're a great spokesman,
by the way.

00:16:12.500 --> 00:16:13.800
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
You know -- thank you --

00:16:13.800 --> 00:16:18.540
you know, in doing Mutts,
I really, even though Earl

00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:21.330
and Mooch talk, I really
wanted it to, people to connect

00:16:21.330 --> 00:16:23.590
with their own cat and dog
because if you have a cat

00:16:23.590 --> 00:16:25.280
and dog, you all know
how funny they are.

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:29.060
They -- I'm sure everyone's
cat and dog can be a cartoon.

00:16:29.060 --> 00:16:32.550
And they're based on my memories
of different cats I've had

00:16:32.550 --> 00:16:36.130
and the dog and cat I have now.

00:16:36.130 --> 00:16:38.780
And, you know, I just
thought that I was trying

00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:41.570
to see the world
through their eyes,

00:16:41.570 --> 00:16:43.140
and trying to see the
world through their eyes,

00:16:43.140 --> 00:16:45.650
I realized how tough a lot of
animals have it on this planet,

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:49.030
so I just wanted that
to become part of Mutts.

00:16:49.030 --> 00:16:50.810
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Let's tell
some more of their stories.

00:16:50.810 --> 00:16:52.600
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Yeah, so this is Sky.

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:55.570
"Sure, I know I'm deaf, but I'd
still make a great companion.

00:16:55.570 --> 00:16:58.830
Just do like I do:
Listen to your heart."

00:16:58.830 --> 00:17:00.130
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: The faces.

00:17:00.130 --> 00:17:02.270
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: I put
that one in particularly

00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:07.830
because I got a letter
from a policewoman,

00:17:07.830 --> 00:17:11.250
and she said she just did a
drug raid, and in the drug raid,

00:17:11.250 --> 00:17:15.590
there was a deaf pit bull that
she had to take to the shelter,

00:17:15.590 --> 00:17:18.810
but she was just really attached
to this dog that she had

00:17:18.810 --> 00:17:23.590
to bring to the shelter, and
she didn't know what to do,

00:17:23.590 --> 00:17:27.350
but she came home, relaxed,
took out the newspaper,

00:17:27.350 --> 00:17:29.830
and that strip was in the
paper the day she did that.

00:17:29.830 --> 00:17:31.130
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Oh, my.

00:17:31.130 --> 00:17:32.430
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: And
she literally went back

00:17:32.430 --> 00:17:34.330
to the shelter, and adopted
that dog, and named him Sky.

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:36.510
So you never know how
you might touch somebody.

00:17:36.510 --> 00:17:37.810
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Saving lives.

00:17:37.810 --> 00:17:39.110
I'm not kidding.

00:17:39.110 --> 00:17:40.410
I'm not kidding.

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:41.710
Okay.

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:43.010
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: And this
is another one, Sweetness.

00:17:43.010 --> 00:17:44.310
"Tom and Karina drove 3
hours to come and adopt me.

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:47.070
They saw me in my
shelter, in my sweater

00:17:47.070 --> 00:17:48.370
on the shelter's website.

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:49.680
It was love at first sight.

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:51.020
Likewise."

00:17:51.020 --> 00:17:54.250
And this was another opportunity
that I got to go to spend a,

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:57.910
2 days at the New York City
shelter and did stories

00:17:57.910 --> 00:17:59.780
about real things, and
that was a real story.

00:17:59.780 --> 00:18:03.180
Someone drove 3 hours from
Vermont or Maine, I think,

00:18:03.180 --> 00:18:05.530
to adopt this dog in New York.

00:18:06.580 --> 00:18:07.880
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:09.180
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Chickpea
and Chickpea's brother.

00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:10.480
"Well, the shelter's
closing up for another day.

00:18:10.480 --> 00:18:11.780
We didn't get picked."

00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:13.080
"I know. Tomorrow, guaranteed."

00:18:13.080 --> 00:18:14.840
I did this story about
Chickpea and Chickpea's brother

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:16.140
in the shelter, and at
the end of the week,

00:18:16.140 --> 00:18:19.480
they didn't get adopted, and
I got a lot of nasty letters.

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:24.490
So a couple of months later,
I had them both adopted.

00:18:24.490 --> 00:18:25.790
And Guard Dog.

00:18:25.790 --> 00:18:27.090
I always get letters
about Guard Dog.

00:18:27.090 --> 00:18:28.390
They want me to free him.

00:18:28.390 --> 00:18:29.920
And someday, I definitely
will, but for now,

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:31.910
I feel like he has
a message to say

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:35.040
for people who chain their dogs.

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:37.970
And hopefully, more and more
states are outlawing that.

00:18:37.970 --> 00:18:39.270
So, "Beware of dog.

00:18:39.270 --> 00:18:42.340
I might break your heart."

00:18:42.340 --> 00:18:44.990
This is a strip I did a few
years ago, Sweet Dreams.

00:18:44.990 --> 00:18:48.610
And in the first panel, Millie's
petting Mooch in her home.

00:18:48.610 --> 00:18:50.370
But in the second
panel, we have pigs

00:18:50.370 --> 00:18:53.520
in crates wishing they
were running free,

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:55.750
an elephant in the circus
wishing he was running free,

00:18:55.750 --> 00:18:59.020
chickens in battery cages
wishes they were running free,

00:18:59.020 --> 00:19:01.130
chimps in the laboratory
wishing they were running free,

00:19:01.130 --> 00:19:02.680
and then ends with
Guard Dog wishing

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:04.480
that he was getting
sweet dreams.

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:06.840
What's amazing about this
strip, I did it quite a,

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:11.490
like 10 years ago or maybe even
longer, and, you know, progress.

00:19:11.490 --> 00:19:14.260
You know, Barnum &amp; Bailey
don't have elephants

00:19:14.260 --> 00:19:15.560
in the circus anymore.

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:17.360
Like, things are
definitely getting better,

00:19:17.360 --> 00:19:20.240
and there's optimism that
the world will start having

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:21.540
more empathy.

00:19:21.540 --> 00:19:22.840
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:24.140
And then, here.

00:19:24.140 --> 00:19:25.730
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: "I'm going
to get you, I'm going to let you

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:27.030
in on a little secret.

00:19:27.030 --> 00:19:28.360
Millions of chickens are
kept in cages so small,

00:19:28.360 --> 00:19:29.670
they can't even spread
their wings.

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:30.970
Now you know."

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:34.620
And that was done, California
was passing a proposition

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:39.410
to let chickens in cages
actually have more space,

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:41.520
and so I wanted to be
part of that message,

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:45.350
and they actually
voted that through.

00:19:45.350 --> 00:19:47.360
So the power of the comic strip.

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:48.660
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:19:48.660 --> 00:19:50.160
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
I'm going veggie.

00:19:50.160 --> 00:19:51.460
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yes.

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:52.760
You've gone veggie
yourself, right?

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:54.060
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Yeah,
that, I tell you, the,

00:19:54.060 --> 00:19:55.360
more and more, I feel
like that's what's going

00:19:55.360 --> 00:19:56.660
to change this planet.

00:19:56.660 --> 00:19:58.560
I mean, even if you just
did Meatless Monday,

00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:00.370
you could help millions
of animals.

00:20:00.370 --> 00:20:03.090
It's amazing how many
animals are killed for that,

00:20:03.090 --> 00:20:06.590
so I thought we could
do that message.

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:09.930
I started out with only eating
-- my wife and I, 40 years ago

00:20:09.930 --> 00:20:11.950
or 30 years ago, said,

00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:13.940
let's just have meat
1 day, once a day.

00:20:13.940 --> 00:20:15.720
And then, it became once a week.

00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:17.020
And then, we just got off it.

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:19.250
And now, we've been vegan
for quite a few years.

00:20:19.250 --> 00:20:20.820
And it just gets
easier and easier.

00:20:20.820 --> 00:20:22.560
We went to a great vegan
restaurant right here

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:25.500
in Washington, D.C. for
breakfast, so it gets easier,

00:20:25.500 --> 00:20:27.000
and I think that's what's
going to change the world.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:28.700
There's more and
more vegan products

00:20:28.700 --> 00:20:30.490
that everybody could enjoy.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:31.790
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:20:31.790 --> 00:20:33.090
We had to shut a few
concession stands right out here

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:35.100
when you came up [laughs]
just to make sure.

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:36.400
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: I'm sure.

00:20:36.400 --> 00:20:37.700
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:20:37.700 --> 00:20:40.140
And then, similar, you
know, talking about planet

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:42.800
and just the larger
picture there.

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:44.100
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Well, like I said,

00:20:44.100 --> 00:20:45.940
when you start seeing the
world through animals' eyes,

00:20:45.940 --> 00:20:47.240
you see how tough it is.

00:20:47.240 --> 00:20:50.850
I mean, there's so, we have so
much plastic in our oceans now.

00:20:50.850 --> 00:20:54.520
See animals are dying from
being choked with plastic.

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:55.820
So I did this strip.

00:20:55.820 --> 00:20:58.990
And I, actually, there's
a guy in I think Arizona

00:20:58.990 --> 00:21:01.770
who just wrote to me that
he's spending his life trying

00:21:01.770 --> 00:21:03.490
to solve that problem.

00:21:03.490 --> 00:21:06.190
And he said it because he
was reading Mutts as a kid

00:21:06.190 --> 00:21:08.110
since he was 5 years old.

00:21:08.110 --> 00:21:11.800
So you never know who you're
going to, who you might touch.

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:13.560
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Did
you mail back thank-sch?

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:15.520
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: No, I'm
going to send him the original.

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:16.820
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:21:16.820 --> 00:21:18.850
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: So this is
a comic I did a few years back

00:21:18.850 --> 00:21:22.240
where Noodles says
to, Shtinky says

00:21:22.240 --> 00:21:23.540
to Noodles, "Yes, Mr. Noodles.

00:21:23.540 --> 00:21:25.260
Sometimes I do get
compassion fatigue."

00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:27.110
"Gee, Jules, how do you get
over something like that?"

00:21:27.110 --> 00:21:31.030
"Well, my autographed photo
of Dr. Jane Goodall helps."

00:21:31.030 --> 00:21:32.380
[laughter] And that
appeared in the paper,

00:21:32.380 --> 00:21:34.380
and the Jane Goodall
Institute called me and said,

00:21:34.380 --> 00:21:35.880
can we put that on
our newsletter?

00:21:35.880 --> 00:21:38.000
And I said, you can do
anything you want with it.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.910
I'd love to send you the
original to give to Jane.

00:21:40.910 --> 00:21:42.210
And they said, well,
Jane's going to be

00:21:42.210 --> 00:21:43.510
in New York next week.

00:21:43.510 --> 00:21:44.810
Why don't you just give
it to Jane herself?

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:46.140
I said, oh, okay.

00:21:46.140 --> 00:21:48.550
So I got to meet Jane,
which inspired me

00:21:48.550 --> 00:21:51.980
to do a children's book on
Jane Goodall called Me...

00:21:51.980 --> 00:21:53.280
Jane.

00:21:53.280 --> 00:21:55.210
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: The Caldecott
Medal winning children's book.

00:21:55.210 --> 00:21:56.510
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: Yeah.

00:21:56.510 --> 00:21:59.910
Yeah, thank you.

00:21:59.910 --> 00:22:02.310
[applause] And, you know,
it's a love letter to Jane,

00:22:02.310 --> 00:22:04.820
but since we're here
at the book festival,

00:22:04.820 --> 00:22:06.130
it's a love letter to books.

00:22:06.130 --> 00:22:08.230
I mean, the power of books,
you know, part of that,

00:22:08.230 --> 00:22:11.870
that's an auto, a biography
about Jane as a young girl,

00:22:11.870 --> 00:22:16.270
and she just talks about
reading Tarzan and Dr. Dolittle,

00:22:16.270 --> 00:22:19.820
and it was those books in her
childhood that made her dream

00:22:19.820 --> 00:22:21.810
of going to Africa and
working with animals.

00:22:21.810 --> 00:22:23.860
So, boy, just the
power of books.

00:22:23.860 --> 00:22:26.440
I'm sure everyone here has a
book that changed their lives,

00:22:26.440 --> 00:22:29.020
and I think that's why
we come here and read.

00:22:29.020 --> 00:22:30.320
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:33.580
Did you have a book or books
that changed your life early on?

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:35.160
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: You know,
probably Come Home, Snoopy.

00:22:35.160 --> 00:22:38.460
[laughs] You know,
that was my religion.

00:22:38.460 --> 00:22:42.940
Before I went to bed, I read
those Peanuts paperbacks.

00:22:42.940 --> 00:22:44.240
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:22:44.240 --> 00:22:45.540
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: So, yeah,

00:22:45.540 --> 00:22:47.450
that was what changed my
-- you know, like Jane.

00:22:47.450 --> 00:22:49.990
I mean, Jane at 4 years old
knew she was going to do that,

00:22:49.990 --> 00:22:51.290
and I think at 4 years old,

00:22:51.290 --> 00:22:53.330
I knew I wanted to
draw comic strips.

00:22:53.330 --> 00:22:54.740
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And
then, it all came together.

00:22:54.740 --> 00:22:56.040
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Dreams can come true.

00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:57.340
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Her, Jane.

00:22:57.340 --> 00:22:58.640
You, Patrick.

00:22:58.640 --> 00:22:59.940
And that's made for books.

00:22:59.940 --> 00:23:02.870
Well, it is now time to
welcome 2 more nature lovers

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:06.810
and animal lovers to our
stage, and they'll get a chance

00:23:06.810 --> 00:23:08.530
to talk with Patrick too.

00:23:08.530 --> 00:23:14.130
The first is Tillie Walden, who,
2 years ago, 2016, you know,

00:23:14.130 --> 00:23:16.100
right up the road, we
heard Sarah talking

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:17.460
about Small Press Expo.

00:23:17.460 --> 00:23:18.760
If you live in the area,

00:23:18.760 --> 00:23:21.170
if you're around the
area -- there she is.

00:23:21.170 --> 00:23:22.470
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Hi, hi.

00:23:22.470 --> 00:23:23.770
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Thank you, Tillie.

00:23:23.770 --> 00:23:25.070
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell:
Nice to meet you.

00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:26.370
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Well,

00:23:26.370 --> 00:23:27.670
let's give Tillie Walden
and Penelope Bagieu.

00:23:27.670 --> 00:23:29.210
[applause] Thank you guys.

00:23:29.210 --> 00:23:33.450
So while they get mic-ed up,
so Tillie, if you get a chance

00:23:33.450 --> 00:23:35.590
to go to Small Press
Expo, she won not 1,

00:23:35.590 --> 00:23:40.580
but 2 Ignatz Awards 2 years ago,
and it's a great place to see

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:42.490
who the, where the
rising stars are.

00:23:42.490 --> 00:23:48.060
At the time, she was 20 and
just continued to do great work.

00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:50.350
Then, last year, she
came out with Spinning,

00:23:50.350 --> 00:23:53.920
which just weeks ago won an
Eisner Award, which is the Oscar

00:23:53.920 --> 00:23:55.800
of comics, so that's huge.

00:23:55.800 --> 00:24:00.750
She has lived in a number of
places, but Texas is her home

00:24:00.750 --> 00:24:02.120
and where she was from.

00:24:02.120 --> 00:24:04.660
You went to the Center for
Cartoon Studies to study

00:24:04.660 --> 00:24:09.060
with the great James Sturm,
and it's a great place.

00:24:09.060 --> 00:24:12.360
If you have a child or someone
close to you and they want

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:14.150
to become a cartoonist
and get serious,

00:24:14.150 --> 00:24:17.150
the Center for Cartoon
Studies up in Vermont is one

00:24:17.150 --> 00:24:19.080
of the great places to land.

00:24:19.080 --> 00:24:25.200
And so we have Spinning, and
we also have her new book comes

00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:30.280
out in October, On a Sunbeam,
and I got to read a preview

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:32.690
of it, and I can't
recommend it more highly.

00:24:32.690 --> 00:24:35.300
So you've done 4 graphic novels.

00:24:35.300 --> 00:24:36.950
You had your web comic come out.

00:24:36.950 --> 00:24:39.510
The great Brian K.
Vaughan, cartoonist, said,

00:24:39.510 --> 00:24:42.600
"Tillie Walden is the
future of comics."

00:24:42.600 --> 00:24:45.620
And we have 2 people here
are the future of comics.

00:24:45.620 --> 00:24:49.630
With Penelope Bagieu, who this
is the third time I've had the

00:24:49.630 --> 00:24:50.970
pleasure of moderating you

00:24:50.970 --> 00:24:53.460
because she is a true
rock star in comic.

00:24:53.460 --> 00:24:55.030
She's a rock star in France.

00:24:55.030 --> 00:24:57.320
She also is in a
rock band, so that,

00:24:57.320 --> 00:24:59.930
she has, she's, that is she.

00:24:59.930 --> 00:25:02.870
She, her blog, My
Quite Fascinating Life,

00:25:02.870 --> 00:25:05.950
started drawing great
attention in France.

00:25:05.950 --> 00:25:07.830
Then, she, you know, I'm
not even going to try

00:25:07.830 --> 00:25:09.130
to pronounce this French.

00:25:09.130 --> 00:25:11.610
I had French, and I don't want
to mangle one of your titles.

00:25:11.610 --> 00:25:14.480
But in English, it is
Brazen: Rebel Ladies

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:17.220
Who Rocked the World,
which came out this year.

00:25:17.220 --> 00:25:20.530
One critic called it
"beguilingly brilliant."

00:25:20.530 --> 00:25:21.830
Wait, that was me.

00:25:21.830 --> 00:25:25.670
I reviewed it and wrote
"beguilingly brilliant."

00:25:25.670 --> 00:25:28.000
[laughter] You know, to quote
yourself is always good.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:33.320
But she did, she came out with
the graphic novel Exquisite

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:35.200
Corpse, which is wonderful.

00:25:35.200 --> 00:25:36.990
Last year, she was here for,

00:25:36.990 --> 00:25:40.910
in the area for California
Dreamin', which is the story

00:25:40.910 --> 00:25:43.530
of Mama Cass Elliot
because even in France,

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:46.760
her parents would play
American rock music on cassettes

00:25:46.760 --> 00:25:50.160
or 8-track, and she was
hearing the Mamas &amp; Papas.

00:25:50.160 --> 00:25:51.850
So Mama Cass Elliot,
if you don't know,

00:25:51.850 --> 00:25:53.690
grew up in this area,
was in Northern Virginia,

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:56.840
then in Baltimore, and
she beautifully tells,

00:25:56.840 --> 00:25:58.290
you know, that story.

00:25:58.290 --> 00:25:59.590
And we'll talk about
her new one.

00:25:59.590 --> 00:26:01.820
But 1, while we're
up here, so Patrick,

00:26:01.820 --> 00:26:04.880
we've heard how much he loves
animals and how much it,

00:26:04.880 --> 00:26:06.820
through his art, you show that.

00:26:06.820 --> 00:26:09.800
Tillie's bio literally
says, "I love cats."

00:26:09.800 --> 00:26:11.100
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: It does.

00:26:11.100 --> 00:26:12.420
I felt like I should
just be clear about it.

00:26:12.420 --> 00:26:13.720
[laughter]

00:26:13.720 --> 00:26:15.020
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Be upfront.

00:26:15.020 --> 00:26:18.500
So, and you have said, Penelope,
that you love nature shows,

00:26:18.500 --> 00:26:22.010
so can you talk, you guys,
just a little bit about,

00:26:22.010 --> 00:26:25.850
with animals, is there an
animal that you turn to,

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:27.890
either personally, or animals,

00:26:27.890 --> 00:26:31.560
a breed that kind of
inspires your art?

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:34.570
I mean, I haven't asked you cat
versus dog because that's, like,

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:35.870
you know, the worst --

00:26:35.870 --> 00:26:37.660
we're already divided
enough in this country.

00:26:37.660 --> 00:26:38.960
I don't want to go there.

00:26:38.960 --> 00:26:41.120
But can you guys talk
about the animals and art?

00:26:41.120 --> 00:26:43.070
Do they inspire you?

00:26:43.070 --> 00:26:46.250
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah, I, I'm
obviously very inspired by cats.

00:26:46.250 --> 00:26:48.420
I think they're wonderful
and fascinating creatures.

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:51.930
And I think when
you're drawing a story,

00:26:51.930 --> 00:26:53.890
especially a graphic
novel, and you want

00:26:53.890 --> 00:26:56.500
to tell the audience
something about your character,

00:26:56.500 --> 00:26:59.070
have that character
interact with a cat.

00:26:59.070 --> 00:27:00.370
Like, I'm serious.

00:27:00.370 --> 00:27:01.670
It says a lot about
who they are.

00:27:01.670 --> 00:27:03.190
You know, do they
immediate go for the snuggle?

00:27:03.190 --> 00:27:04.920
Do they talk to them
like they're a senator?

00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:07.440
Do they, you know,
like, how do we do this?

00:27:07.440 --> 00:27:11.220
And I love using animals as a
way to express who people are

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:13.040
and how they show love.

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:14.340
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:27:14.340 --> 00:27:15.640
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
There's a theory saying

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:17.590
that if you want a character
to look immediately mean

00:27:17.590 --> 00:27:21.180
and for people to hate
him, he has to kill a cat.

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:22.730
And if someone kills a cat--

00:27:22.730 --> 00:27:24.030
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I
would never draw that.

00:27:24.030 --> 00:27:25.330
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: No matter
what you write afterwards,

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:27.190
your readers will hate
him no matter what, and,

00:27:27.190 --> 00:27:29.890
or if he saves a cat,
then he's a good guy

00:27:29.890 --> 00:27:31.190
for the rest of the book.

00:27:31.190 --> 00:27:32.660
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So
that's a signifier

00:27:32.660 --> 00:27:34.180
with how you treat a cat.

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:36.460
Wow. Well, I know Patrick
talked about, you know,

00:27:36.460 --> 00:27:38.350
the work you've done
in terms of, like,

00:27:38.350 --> 00:27:41.210
drawing about marine
conservation and the planet.

00:27:41.210 --> 00:27:44.090
And you actually got,
what, thousands of people

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:46.580
to sign about, it was, had to do

00:27:46.580 --> 00:27:48.330
with the saving marine
life, right.

00:27:48.330 --> 00:27:51.080
Can you talk a little,
just a moment about that?

00:27:51.080 --> 00:27:52.610
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah,
there's a fishing technique,

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:54.660
and industrial fishing
technique all

00:27:54.660 --> 00:27:57.890
over the world called
deep-sea fish trolling,

00:27:57.890 --> 00:28:00.840
which is very destructive
to the Earth.

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:05.160
And there was supposed to
be a law that would be voted

00:28:05.160 --> 00:28:07.150
against this, and
a lot of countries

00:28:07.150 --> 00:28:11.790
for not super clear reasons were
against the banning of this,

00:28:11.790 --> 00:28:14.680
and so I met this woman from
an NGO who's been fighting

00:28:14.680 --> 00:28:16.040
against this all her life,

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:19.190
but she couldn't really
make people care about this

00:28:19.190 --> 00:28:23.020
because it is not a very
sexy subject, honestly.

00:28:23.020 --> 00:28:29.190
So, and so I made a comic online
about this because there was,

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:31.710
we were just about
to have a vote

00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:33.820
at the European Parliament
about this.

00:28:33.820 --> 00:28:38.160
And so she made this petition
online, and she had a hard time,

00:28:38.160 --> 00:28:41.130
yeah, raising attention
from people.

00:28:41.130 --> 00:28:42.940
And so she had maybe,
I don't know,

00:28:42.940 --> 00:28:46.180
I think it was 14,000
signatures to her petition.

00:28:46.180 --> 00:28:49.130
So we made this comic
online, and within the month,

00:28:49.130 --> 00:28:51.030
we had a million signatures.

00:28:51.030 --> 00:28:54.950
So that was very,
yeah, that was nice,

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:57.750
except that still
they voted against it.

00:28:57.750 --> 00:29:02.540
Yeah, so, but that taught me a
lot about how democracy works.

00:29:02.540 --> 00:29:03.840
[laughs]

00:29:03.840 --> 00:29:05.700
&gt;&gt; Patrick McDonnell: It's
also the power of comics that,

00:29:05.700 --> 00:29:07.890
you know, we talk to
people at their level.

00:29:07.890 --> 00:29:10.360
It's like more of a
family conversation,

00:29:10.360 --> 00:29:13.700
and you can really say a
lot of important things

00:29:13.700 --> 00:29:16.340
that people will take
easily than, you know,

00:29:16.340 --> 00:29:17.720
so that's the power of comics.

00:29:17.720 --> 00:29:19.020
You did a great thing.

00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:20.320
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: That's it.

00:29:20.320 --> 00:29:23.170
Well, on that note, we have to
say goodbye to Mr. McDonnell,

