You can sit where you
can, however you want to--

00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:43.770
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
Because that's weird.

00:29:43.770 --> 00:29:45.070
Just kidding.

00:29:45.070 --> 00:29:46.370
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I'm
not going to do that.

00:29:46.370 --> 00:29:47.670
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: We, no.

00:29:47.670 --> 00:29:48.970
[laughs] That's a
later show, and,

00:29:48.970 --> 00:29:50.340
but cats, we need cats up here.

00:29:50.340 --> 00:29:51.660
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
Let's get cozy.

00:29:51.660 --> 00:29:53.680
Oh no. We've ruined
their whole setup for us.

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:54.980
Sorry, guys.

00:29:54.980 --> 00:29:56.280
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: I know.

00:29:56.280 --> 00:29:57.580
I know. But--

00:29:57.580 --> 00:29:58.880
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Rebels.

00:29:58.880 --> 00:30:00.180
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yes.

00:30:00.180 --> 00:30:03.150
So, you know, I don't know if
you were anticipating, you know,

00:30:03.150 --> 00:30:07.180
even though the hash, the "me
too" hashtag was a decade old,

00:30:07.180 --> 00:30:13.350
but where we are now, but the
culture is just so, you know,

00:30:13.350 --> 00:30:17.560
so ready and hungry as
ever to hear these stories.

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:20.100
When you thought about
and obviously came

00:30:20.100 --> 00:30:23.130
out in France first, but with
Brazen, when you started this,

00:30:23.130 --> 00:30:26.180
were you sensing
shifts in the culture,

00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:28.660
or was your timing
just impeccable?

00:30:28.660 --> 00:30:33.300
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: [laughter]
No, there was a long pre process

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:36.250
to it, so I would've loved
to do this book 10 years ago,

00:30:36.250 --> 00:30:40.300
but it just had to, you
know, mature a bit more.

00:30:40.300 --> 00:30:45.100
But then, yes, obviously,
my editor wouldn't deny it.

00:30:45.100 --> 00:30:46.590
The timing was perfect.

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:49.300
[laughs] But it's just
that it took me a long time

00:30:49.300 --> 00:30:52.960
to gather all these
stories, so that was--

00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:54.340
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Twenty-nine, no, they're great,

00:30:54.340 --> 00:30:55.830
and it's a great
array of stories.

00:30:55.830 --> 00:30:57.130
But let me ask.

00:30:57.130 --> 00:30:58.430
You mention your editor.

00:30:58.430 --> 00:31:01.610
You guys both are at First
Second Books, which, you know,

00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:04.050
is just a marvelous imprint.

00:31:04.050 --> 00:31:07.170
What is in the water there that
not only do they draw such,

00:31:07.170 --> 00:31:10.440
having such a great eye for
talent, like such with both

00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:15.710
of you, but the editors seem to
draw out that talent so well?

00:31:15.710 --> 00:31:18.120
What's First Second
doing right in this time

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:22.700
when so much great work is being
done beyond the big 2 or big 3

00:31:22.700 --> 00:31:24.160
when some people
think of comics?

00:31:24.160 --> 00:31:26.680
But it's just great stories.

00:31:26.680 --> 00:31:28.620
I mean, you know, not
to put you on the spot,

00:31:28.620 --> 00:31:33.800
but what are they drinking
up there that's going right?

00:31:33.800 --> 00:31:35.890
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I think
First Second really understands

00:31:35.890 --> 00:31:38.730
comics, and that's
not actually a given

00:31:38.730 --> 00:31:40.720
with a comics publisher,
necessarily.

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:42.760
There are a lot of book
publishers that now want to get

00:31:42.760 --> 00:31:45.360
into graphic novels, but
they just don't understand

00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:48.730
that it is an extremely
unique medium.

00:31:48.730 --> 00:31:50.220
Very different from prose.

00:31:50.220 --> 00:31:52.320
And I feel like at First
Second, they have worked

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:53.620
with so many cartoonists.

00:31:53.620 --> 00:31:55.510
They have published so many
successful graphic novels

00:31:55.510 --> 00:31:57.590
that they understand what works

00:31:57.590 --> 00:32:00.100
and they understand
how cartoonists work.

00:32:00.100 --> 00:32:04.610
And so it's a very artistic
and kind of loving environment,

00:32:04.610 --> 00:32:08.390
and they just, they have a great
team, and they all really care

00:32:08.390 --> 00:32:10.780
about comics, and they
have good aesthetic,

00:32:10.780 --> 00:32:12.230
good aesthetics, good design.

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:14.320
I don't know what it is, really.

00:32:14.320 --> 00:32:15.960
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Well,
we know that France is one

00:32:15.960 --> 00:32:19.210
of the nations that truly
appreciates comics, and--

00:32:19.210 --> 00:32:20.510
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
That's what I heard.

00:32:20.510 --> 00:32:21.810
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: By the way,

00:32:21.810 --> 00:32:24.210
Mark Siegel at First Second
Books, with his strong ties

00:32:24.210 --> 00:32:27.000
to France, has a great
tie, so he appreciates --

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:28.900
sometimes, I feel like the
United States is still trying

00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:31.010
to catch up with much of the
rest of the world about--

00:32:31.010 --> 00:32:32.310
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: We are.

00:32:32.310 --> 00:32:33.610
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Appreciating, yeah, we're--

00:32:33.610 --> 00:32:34.910
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: No, we are.

00:32:34.910 --> 00:32:36.210
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: It's
going to take us a while.

00:32:36.210 --> 00:32:38.830
Well, let's get to these stories

00:32:38.830 --> 00:32:42.420
and have you tell
specifically about some of them.

00:32:42.420 --> 00:32:46.970
So here are there are 29
stories total, and, you know,

00:32:46.970 --> 00:32:50.710
you have to tell these
biographies quickly,

00:32:50.710 --> 00:32:53.550
and so your pacing
is just magnificent,

00:32:53.550 --> 00:32:56.160
but, you know, and that.

00:32:56.160 --> 00:32:57.620
That's just beautiful.

00:32:57.620 --> 00:32:59.760
That's just gorgeous.

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:03.980
So can you tell me, this
is Mae Jemison, right,

00:33:03.980 --> 00:33:05.590
the first black astronaut

00:33:05.590 --> 00:33:08.300
or the first black
woman to go into space?

00:33:08.300 --> 00:33:09.600
Can you tell her--

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:10.900
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: And to be

00:33:10.900 --> 00:33:12.590
in a Star Trek episode
at the same time.

00:33:12.590 --> 00:33:13.890
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Really?

00:33:13.890 --> 00:33:15.190
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah.

00:33:15.190 --> 00:33:16.490
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So
can you tell, what--

00:33:16.490 --> 00:33:17.790
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: She was
a Star Trek fan, and she--

00:33:17.790 --> 00:33:19.090
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: What
drew you to her story?

00:33:19.090 --> 00:33:20.390
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: What
drew me to her story,

00:33:20.390 --> 00:33:22.980
the fact that she was
afraid of both heights

00:33:22.980 --> 00:33:24.660
and darkness when she was a kid.

00:33:24.660 --> 00:33:25.960
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Wow.

00:33:25.960 --> 00:33:27.260
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

00:33:27.260 --> 00:33:28.560
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
That's amazing.

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:29.860
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: And--

00:33:29.860 --> 00:33:31.160
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:33:31.160 --> 00:33:32.460
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
And she ended up,

00:33:32.460 --> 00:33:33.760
you know, kind of nailing it.

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:35.060
[inaudible]

00:33:35.060 --> 00:33:36.360
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And
then, can you tell us,

00:33:36.360 --> 00:33:37.920
is this the rapper
from Afghanistan?

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:39.970
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah,
this is Sonita Alizadeh.

00:33:39.970 --> 00:33:42.420
She's a young girl who
was supposed to be married

00:33:42.420 --> 00:33:45.670
when she was 10 by her
parents in Afghanistan.

00:33:45.670 --> 00:33:49.660
She grew up under the Taliban,
and so she, and one day,

00:33:49.660 --> 00:33:52.720
she heard an Eminem
song on the radio,

00:33:52.720 --> 00:33:54.070
and she didn't understand
the lyrics,

00:33:54.070 --> 00:33:59.550
but she really got struck by the
rage in the way he was singing.

00:33:59.550 --> 00:34:01.140
And she said that
that's what I want to do,

00:34:01.140 --> 00:34:04.940
so she recorded her own rap
song about forced marriage.

00:34:04.940 --> 00:34:08.650
And she was, back
then, living in Iran,

00:34:08.650 --> 00:34:11.620
where it's illegal
for women to sing.

00:34:11.620 --> 00:34:14.300
And so she put it online.

00:34:14.300 --> 00:34:17.580
She shot a little video,
music video on her own,

00:34:17.580 --> 00:34:18.880
and she put it online.

00:34:18.880 --> 00:34:24.820
And she was awarded a grant
to go and study music in Utah.

00:34:24.820 --> 00:34:29.110
And so she had to escape her
family to come to Utah to work

00:34:29.110 --> 00:34:32.360
on her rap, and she was
17 when she did that,

00:34:32.360 --> 00:34:34.930
which is such a lesson because
I remember what I was doing

00:34:34.930 --> 00:34:36.280
when I was 17, and--

00:34:36.280 --> 00:34:37.580
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
What were you doing?

00:34:37.580 --> 00:34:38.880
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Nothing.

00:34:38.880 --> 00:34:40.280
[laughter] I was
doing nothing, mostly.

00:34:40.280 --> 00:34:41.580
So--

00:34:41.580 --> 00:34:42.880
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
You were saving cats.

00:34:42.880 --> 00:34:44.180
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
Yeah, not even.

00:34:44.180 --> 00:34:45.480
I was watching TV,
so I thought, yeah,

00:34:45.480 --> 00:34:47.290
and she's now -- what's she?

00:34:47.290 --> 00:34:48.590
She's your age.

00:34:48.590 --> 00:34:53.360
She's still very young, and
she's still going on stage now.

00:34:53.360 --> 00:34:54.660
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:34:54.660 --> 00:34:56.740
And to me, what's amazing
is the fact she physically,

00:34:56.740 --> 00:35:00.420
her body was going to
be commerce by age 10.

00:35:00.420 --> 00:35:03.820
You literally, that was
her fate unless, instead,

00:35:03.820 --> 00:35:06.110
she turned her mind
into commerce and art.

00:35:06.110 --> 00:35:08.470
I mean, that's just
a beautiful twist,

00:35:08.470 --> 00:35:11.180
and you tell it well
and quickly.

00:35:11.180 --> 00:35:13.560
And is this Nzinga or--

00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:15.000
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yes, it is.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:16.370
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And what
drew you to her story?

00:35:16.370 --> 00:35:20.040
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: She was
queen of what is now Angola,

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:23.830
and she was really
smart, really witty,

00:35:23.830 --> 00:35:26.280
and she had a very dumb brother.

00:35:26.280 --> 00:35:29.700
But he became king because
he was the only son.

00:35:29.700 --> 00:35:31.840
And when she was born,
the woman who put her

00:35:31.840 --> 00:35:35.500
to the world told her father,
she will became a queen.

00:35:35.500 --> 00:35:38.360
And so she had her
brother killed,

00:35:38.360 --> 00:35:40.350
and so she became a queen.

00:35:40.350 --> 00:35:42.920
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Now, that's gangsta.

00:35:42.920 --> 00:35:44.220
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah.

00:35:44.220 --> 00:35:46.620
[laughs] And she was a
very good peace negotiator,

00:35:46.620 --> 00:35:49.490
and she was very fair and just.

00:35:49.490 --> 00:35:51.780
And she was amazing.

00:35:51.780 --> 00:35:54.320
And she said that she
would never have a husband,

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:55.620
but she would have many lovers.

00:35:55.620 --> 00:35:57.830
And she was really cool.

00:35:57.830 --> 00:36:01.640
And she was a queen until the
age of I think probably --

00:36:01.640 --> 00:36:03.530
well, it's not very well
documented about this --

00:36:03.530 --> 00:36:05.870
but probably around
her late 70s.

00:36:05.870 --> 00:36:07.910
And she was still
on the battlefield,

00:36:07.910 --> 00:36:10.030
on the front row to fight.

00:36:10.030 --> 00:36:11.330
So she's super cool.

00:36:11.330 --> 00:36:12.870
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: A
true woman warrior.

00:36:12.870 --> 00:36:15.100
Yeah. And this is the
bearded lady, right,

00:36:15.100 --> 00:36:16.400
as she was [inaudible].

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:18.200
Can you tell us what, her story?

00:36:18.200 --> 00:36:19.500
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah.

00:36:19.500 --> 00:36:20.800
So her name is Clementine
Delait.

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:24.530
She was the first
bearded supermodel

00:36:24.530 --> 00:36:28.000
because she was a bearded
lady, but she refused to be

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:31.920
in a circus, like in a show,
nor to shave, of course.

00:36:31.920 --> 00:36:36.990
And she said, I don't want
to be part of a freak show.

00:36:36.990 --> 00:36:39.110
I want to be like a freelancer.

00:36:39.110 --> 00:36:43.080
And so she was selling
her autographed pictures

00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:44.990
to her fans.

00:36:44.990 --> 00:36:48.010
And then, she started her own
cabaret in the east of France,

00:36:48.010 --> 00:36:52.110
and she adopted kids, and
she was really amazing.

00:36:52.110 --> 00:36:56.210
But she started her life
by, of course, being shamed

00:36:56.210 --> 00:37:01.330
for her beard, and then she was
offered as the only opportunity

00:37:01.330 --> 00:37:04.810
for a woman like her to
be, yeah, to be a freak.

00:37:04.810 --> 00:37:08.650
And that was early 20th century,

00:37:08.650 --> 00:37:10.960
so there were not
many other options.

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:12.750
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So so far,
every woman we're talking

00:37:12.750 --> 00:37:16.150
about basically was, had been
assigned a role by her birth,

00:37:16.150 --> 00:37:19.190
essentially, and having to
steer hard against that.

00:37:19.190 --> 00:37:20.490
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah.

00:37:20.490 --> 00:37:21.790
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:37:21.790 --> 00:37:24.590
And then, yeah, there we go.

00:37:24.590 --> 00:37:25.990
Try this again.

00:37:25.990 --> 00:37:27.290
Look at her there.

00:37:27.290 --> 00:37:28.590
I love -- look at
that top panel.

00:37:28.590 --> 00:37:29.980
That's just beautiful.

00:37:29.980 --> 00:37:32.560
That's her story.

00:37:34.880 --> 00:37:36.840
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: And even in
France, she's not that famous,

00:37:36.840 --> 00:37:38.760
which I thought was very unfair.

00:37:38.760 --> 00:37:41.030
And that is the thing in common

00:37:41.030 --> 00:37:43.930
for all these women I think
is just that the reaction

00:37:43.930 --> 00:37:48.010
that I had mostly with this
book was people telling me, oh,

00:37:48.010 --> 00:37:50.750
how come I never heard of
that woman, even if she was

00:37:50.750 --> 00:37:52.140
like a Nobel Prize for Peace?

00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:53.820
Because some of them are.

00:37:53.820 --> 00:37:59.290
And as usual, they are
invisible, so I thought,

00:37:59.290 --> 00:38:04.720
in a very proud way, I was
very proud when people say,

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:08.010
I have never heard about
them, and that's my, yeah.

00:38:08.010 --> 00:38:09.310
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yes.

00:38:09.310 --> 00:38:10.610
And it's a great
mix because some

00:38:10.610 --> 00:38:13.320
of the people you may have even
heard of like Josephine Baker,

00:38:13.320 --> 00:38:17.530
known as a club and cabaret,
or Hedy Lamarr, the actress,

00:38:17.530 --> 00:38:20.870
but we didn't know sort of,
when it came to World War II,

00:38:20.870 --> 00:38:25.410
what they were doing, whether in
terms of sleuth work, spy work,

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:27.880
or technology, this
whole other side

00:38:27.880 --> 00:38:29.400
that just never came to light.

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:32.840
Yeah, that's beautiful.

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:34.140
Look at her there.

00:38:34.140 --> 00:38:37.280
And then, so this is
Las Mariposas, right?

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:40.020
Can you tell us about, was
this, and they're Dominican?

00:38:40.020 --> 00:38:42.100
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah,
so they were 4 sisters,

00:38:42.100 --> 00:38:49.230
but 3 of them became
resistant to the local tyrant

00:38:49.230 --> 00:38:51.390
in Dominican Republic.

00:38:51.390 --> 00:38:54.040
And what they had in common
was that they were very smart,

00:38:54.040 --> 00:38:55.780
but they were also
very beautiful,

00:38:55.780 --> 00:39:02.130
and that men had the horrible
habit of kind of going fishing

00:39:02.130 --> 00:39:07.040
for young, beautiful
girls to hang around with.

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:10.290
And so he invited them over
to his sort of palazzo,

00:39:10.290 --> 00:39:15.390
and he was hitting on them,
like, very, very intensely.

00:39:15.390 --> 00:39:18.690
And that's what threw them
into politics because they were

00:39:18.690 --> 00:39:21.800
so sick of being seen as a
piece of meat that they decided

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:24.470
to fight back the power.

00:39:24.470 --> 00:39:26.470
And they were put in jail.

00:39:26.470 --> 00:39:27.770
They were tortured.

00:39:27.770 --> 00:39:34.320
But they still fought him
with all their energy.

00:39:34.320 --> 00:39:36.830
And eventually, they
were murdered.

00:39:36.830 --> 00:39:42.660
And today, the International Day
Against Women Violence, Violent,

00:39:42.660 --> 00:39:45.680
yeah, Violence Against Women is
the day they were killed still,

00:39:45.680 --> 00:39:46.980
so.

00:39:46.980 --> 00:39:49.060
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So they
were, so they became martyrs--

00:39:49.060 --> 00:39:50.360
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah.

00:39:50.360 --> 00:39:51.660
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Essentially.

00:39:51.660 --> 00:39:52.960
Yeah, yeah.

00:39:52.960 --> 00:39:54.260
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: What?

00:39:54.260 --> 00:39:55.560
&gt;&gt; What about the fourth one?

00:39:55.560 --> 00:39:56.900
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: What
happened to the fourth sister?

00:39:56.900 --> 00:39:58.200
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
She was mild.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:00.830
She was not that much
into politics, I think.

00:40:00.830 --> 00:40:02.130
&gt;&gt; She was what?

00:40:02.130 --> 00:40:03.760
She was wild?

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:05.060
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Mild?

00:40:05.060 --> 00:40:06.360
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah,
she was more, you know.

00:40:06.360 --> 00:40:08.710
She had more mild
political stances,

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:10.290
I think, than her sisters.

00:40:10.290 --> 00:40:11.590
So these are the other 2.

00:40:11.590 --> 00:40:13.270
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So she
got to live, basically.

00:40:13.270 --> 00:40:14.580
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
No, she died too.

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:15.880
