00:42:25.640 --> 00:42:26.940
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
It's Nzinga that we--

00:42:26.940 --> 00:42:28.240
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
This is Nzinga, yeah.

00:42:28.240 --> 00:42:29.540
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
Mentioned before, yeah.

00:42:29.540 --> 00:42:30.840
And that's me.

00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:32.140
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
And that is you.

00:42:32.140 --> 00:42:33.440
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: With
a beautiful other picture.

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:34.740
[laughter]

00:42:34.740 --> 00:42:36.040
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: You were
voted the least terrifying woman

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:37.340
in the world in the
most recent--

00:42:37.340 --> 00:42:38.640
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Well,
there's actually my story

00:42:38.640 --> 00:42:40.310
at the end of the book,
which was not my idea

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:42.530
because I thought that
was really pretentious.

00:42:42.530 --> 00:42:45.300
But since we had to remove
1 story from the original

00:42:45.300 --> 00:42:48.560
because it was originally
30 women, and 1 was removed

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:52.680
for the American edition
because it was too hard,

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:53.980
[laughs] so it was removed.

00:42:53.980 --> 00:42:57.320
And so instead, my editor,
our editor suggested

00:42:57.320 --> 00:43:02.430
that I put my own story in it
being told from the outside,

00:43:02.430 --> 00:43:04.660
which is a super
weird experience.

00:43:04.660 --> 00:43:09.070
So I wrote a 2-page comic
to explain how I was brazen

00:43:09.070 --> 00:43:11.820
and cool, so [laughs]
it's horrible,

00:43:11.820 --> 00:43:13.120
but it's still in the book.

00:43:13.120 --> 00:43:14.420
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Does that exist?

00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:15.720
Is that in there?

00:43:15.720 --> 00:43:17.020
Is that--

00:43:17.020 --> 00:43:18.320
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah, it is.

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:19.620
Yeah, it's the last 2 pages, and
it's, and then, Penelope went

00:43:19.620 --> 00:43:20.920
on to become, blah, blah, blah.

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:22.220
And I wrote this, so
this is really weird.

00:43:22.220 --> 00:43:23.520
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Okay, no, I read that.

00:43:23.520 --> 00:43:25.120
It just, okay, it felt humble.

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:26.610
It didn't feel pretentious.

00:43:26.610 --> 00:43:29.920
Okay, that's why -- I was,
I thought there was a comic

00:43:29.920 --> 00:43:31.840
out there where it
was like you were--

00:43:31.840 --> 00:43:33.140
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: No.

00:43:33.140 --> 00:43:34.920
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yes, okay.

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:37.120
[laughs] So with
Tillie, Spinning.

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:39.110
You know, this, it's

00:43:39.110 --> 00:43:41.770
such a beautiful work,
a heartfelt work.

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:43.780
Deeply personal.

00:43:43.780 --> 00:43:46.400
I could sort of mangle
it and try to say,

00:43:46.400 --> 00:43:50.210
explain in 30 words all
-- no, but the drama.

00:43:50.210 --> 00:43:55.050
I mean, what I will say is
what you get, the sheer, raw,

00:43:55.050 --> 00:43:57.830
tender emotion is apparent.

00:43:57.830 --> 00:43:59.130
I've experienced it.

00:43:59.130 --> 00:44:02.510
When you see a teenage
girl, when something that,

00:44:02.510 --> 00:44:05.110
when you're a little
older, is just a mild thing,

00:44:05.110 --> 00:44:09.220
but everything new is,
just feels so immediate

00:44:09.220 --> 00:44:11.710
and can feel incredibly
dramatic,

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:14.030
and your life is upside down.

00:44:14.030 --> 00:44:16.610
So when you're working, I mean,

00:44:16.610 --> 00:44:21.280
you're a competitor junior
skater, and you are, you know,

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:25.120
looking, having, you're
having skating with different,

00:44:25.120 --> 00:44:28.750
in the morning, see a different
girl, one who's 5 years older,

00:44:28.750 --> 00:44:31.280
and you're sensing a
stirring, an attraction.

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:32.580
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Oh, yeah.

00:44:32.580 --> 00:44:33.880
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yes.

00:44:33.880 --> 00:44:35.180
See, right there.

00:44:35.180 --> 00:44:37.840
That "oh, yeah" said more
than my previous 40 words.

00:44:37.840 --> 00:44:40.880
Please, you can do
it better than I.

00:44:40.880 --> 00:44:42.480
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: You
mean describe Spinning.

00:44:42.480 --> 00:44:44.520
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Want
me to describe Spinning

00:44:44.520 --> 00:44:47.570
and then what sort of,
what it's like to be

00:44:47.570 --> 00:44:50.880
that personal on
that level in art.

00:44:50.880 --> 00:44:53.690
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
It's kind of awful.

00:44:53.690 --> 00:44:55.430
It's very hard to make a memoir,

00:44:55.430 --> 00:44:58.360
and I think no matter what age
you are, it's very hard to look

00:44:58.360 --> 00:45:04.790
at yourself with
honesty and bravery.

00:45:04.790 --> 00:45:08.560
And Spinning is, it's
about my childhood.

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:10.350
I grew up as a competitive
figure skater.

00:45:10.350 --> 00:45:13.140
I did synchronized
skating as well.

00:45:13.140 --> 00:45:14.450
Not a lot of people
know what synchro is.

00:45:14.450 --> 00:45:16.700
And I grew up in New
Jersey and Texas.

00:45:16.700 --> 00:45:18.000
And I'm also a lesbian.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:20.350
And I felt like I was breaking
into this thing where it was

00:45:20.350 --> 00:45:24.680
like not only are almost all
skating narratives just awful,

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:26.600
and really boring, and
stupid, and they end

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:28.160
with them getting a gold medal.

00:45:28.160 --> 00:45:30.570
And, like, oh, look, a cute
guy on the side of the rink.

00:45:30.570 --> 00:45:31.870
And I was like, oh, gross.

00:45:31.870 --> 00:45:33.910
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: [laughs]
That's not your rom-com.

00:45:33.910 --> 00:45:35.210
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: No.

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:37.810
I was like, I have been, I
grew up being so frustrated

00:45:37.810 --> 00:45:41.370
with skating media and very
frustrated with sports media

00:45:41.370 --> 00:45:44.940
that I wanted to tell a story
about what it means to grow

00:45:44.940 --> 00:45:47.270
up in a sport, what it means
to grow up being pushed

00:45:47.270 --> 00:45:50.930
to do something that you are
good at and that you also hate,

00:45:50.930 --> 00:45:54.560
and then also to be a
lesbian while doing that.

00:45:54.560 --> 00:45:55.860
And that--

00:45:55.860 --> 00:45:57.160
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
And discovering.

00:45:57.160 --> 00:45:58.460
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: And
discovering that, and figuring

00:45:58.460 --> 00:46:00.520
that out in the locker room,
and trying to decide whether

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:04.990
or not these girls would let me
come back in this locker room

00:46:04.990 --> 00:46:06.290
if they knew I was a lesbian.

00:46:06.290 --> 00:46:07.590
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:46:07.590 --> 00:46:11.100
Well, at 1 point, I
think you actually say,

00:46:11.100 --> 00:46:12.990
you feared acknowledging
you were gay

00:46:12.990 --> 00:46:14.920
or you feared that awakening.

00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:16.620
Or you even talk about fearing,

00:46:16.620 --> 00:46:19.840
not writing gay characters
because of that.

00:46:19.840 --> 00:46:21.140
Like, you had to--

00:46:21.140 --> 00:46:22.440
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Oh, yeah.

00:46:22.440 --> 00:46:23.800
Yeah, I spent, when I first
started drawing comics,

00:46:23.800 --> 00:46:25.340
all my characters
were little boys.

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:26.640
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:46:26.640 --> 00:46:27.940
[laughs]

00:46:27.940 --> 00:46:29.240
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: And I
guess they were straight.

00:46:29.240 --> 00:46:30.540
I have no idea, but it
was all this just kind

00:46:30.540 --> 00:46:31.840
of internalized stuff.

00:46:31.840 --> 00:46:33.740
I spent my whole life seeing
media that told these kinds

00:46:33.740 --> 00:46:36.990
of stories, so when I sat down
to tell stories, naturally,

00:46:36.990 --> 00:46:40.090
I told, I reflected them
back, the things I had seen.

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:42.100
And you, I think there
has to be a moment

00:46:42.100 --> 00:46:44.040
where you say to
yourself, hold on.

00:46:44.040 --> 00:46:45.440
What is important to me?

00:46:45.440 --> 00:46:47.430
What do I actually want to say?

00:46:47.430 --> 00:46:49.730
And you have to push yourself
to put that in your comics.

00:46:49.730 --> 00:46:51.030
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:46:51.030 --> 00:46:52.570
And I should point
out, it wasn't just

00:46:52.570 --> 00:46:53.870
that you were skating.

00:46:53.870 --> 00:46:55.170
This was a 12-year saga.

00:46:55.170 --> 00:46:56.470
I mean, this is hard core.

00:46:56.470 --> 00:46:57.770
This is--

00:46:57.770 --> 00:46:59.070
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I
was skating far longer

00:46:59.070 --> 00:47:00.370
than I've been drawing.

00:47:00.370 --> 00:47:01.670
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

00:47:01.670 --> 00:47:02.970
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I'm a much
more accomplished skater

00:47:02.970 --> 00:47:04.270
than I am an accomplished
artist.

00:47:04.270 --> 00:47:05.570
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: No, no, no.

00:47:05.570 --> 00:47:06.870
But I love the way, you know,
different chapter titles,

00:47:06.870 --> 00:47:10.130
the way you have axel,
or lutz, or counter.

00:47:10.130 --> 00:47:12.410
And so what that
hammers home is it's not,

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:14.290
you describe the technical move,

00:47:14.290 --> 00:47:17.530
but then you realize that's
also an emotional state.

00:47:17.530 --> 00:47:21.380
And it just works beautifully
on that level because you sense,

00:47:21.380 --> 00:47:25.740
you know, it feels like
as you're discovering it,

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:27.870
we're so in the moment with you.

00:47:27.870 --> 00:47:29.570
We're feeling with
you moment to moment.

00:47:29.570 --> 00:47:32.030
Oh, there's Lindsay,
and here comes Caitlin,

00:47:32.030 --> 00:47:35.120
and there's Molly, and there's,
you know, and there's Ray,

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:38.890
and then, is Grace sort of
your nemesis, would you say?

00:47:38.890 --> 00:47:40.190
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah, yeah.

00:47:40.190 --> 00:47:41.490
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:42.790
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I mean, some
of the book is about bullying

00:47:42.790 --> 00:47:44.490
and things I experienced.

00:47:44.490 --> 00:47:46.430
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So here,
the massiveness of a rank,

00:47:46.430 --> 00:47:47.830
and there you are back again.

00:47:47.830 --> 00:47:49.130
You talk about--

00:47:49.130 --> 00:47:50.430
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Well,
and what's strange is

00:47:50.430 --> 00:47:54.520
that I didn't use any photo
reference for this book.

00:47:54.520 --> 00:47:57.010
I, because I just, I
wanted the drawings

00:47:57.010 --> 00:47:58.820
to reflect how I
remembered things.

00:47:58.820 --> 00:48:01.210
Like, if you all think back
to your childhood home,

00:48:01.210 --> 00:48:03.560
in your mind, it's a lot
bigger than it actually was

00:48:03.560 --> 00:48:07.230
because when you're a kid,
everything seems huge to you,

00:48:07.230 --> 00:48:09.270
and I wanted the scenes to
feel like those memories.

00:48:09.270 --> 00:48:11.410
But that rink, I drew
it in this huge way,

00:48:11.410 --> 00:48:13.760
and when I finished the
book, I actually looked

00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:15.060
up what it looked like.

00:48:15.060 --> 00:48:16.360
It is that big.

00:48:16.360 --> 00:48:17.660
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

00:48:17.660 --> 00:48:18.960
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
I wasn't wrong.

00:48:18.960 --> 00:48:20.260
It's huge, and there's
an American flag in it.

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:21.560
I was right.

00:48:21.560 --> 00:48:22.860
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So
draw it when you're 20,

00:48:22.860 --> 00:48:24.160
not when you're 40,
is what you're saying.

00:48:24.160 --> 00:48:25.460
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Or
draw whenever you want.

00:48:25.460 --> 00:48:26.760
Who cares.

00:48:26.760 --> 00:48:28.060
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: [laughs]
But your sense of it.

00:48:28.060 --> 00:48:30.220
And it's just, and, you know, by
the way, on a technical level,

00:48:30.220 --> 00:48:33.110
your grid work, you know,
the way you'll do 6 panel,

00:48:33.110 --> 00:48:37.560
and then you have these 24-panel
pages, it's, on the ice,

00:48:37.560 --> 00:48:40.440
it's just heart -- I mean,
you feel the immediate.

00:48:40.440 --> 00:48:44.720
It also reminded me because I
was just a, on a much less so,

00:48:44.720 --> 00:48:48.280
I was a competitive junior, as
a kid, junior tennis player.

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:52.370
And, but I wasn't thinking
about my makeup, and I wasn't,

00:48:52.370 --> 00:48:54.030
use your wording,
I wasn't thinking

00:48:54.030 --> 00:48:57.340
about whether my crotch was
showing as I'm doing a move.

00:48:57.340 --> 00:49:00.750
And I wasn't worrying about,
you know, just concerns

00:49:00.750 --> 00:49:04.130
that I've covered both men's
and women's sports early

00:49:04.130 --> 00:49:07.030
in my career, and the
difference, you make us aware

00:49:07.030 --> 00:49:09.250
of everything in those panels.

00:49:09.250 --> 00:49:13.940
And it just, everything feels
just painfully, and it feels

00:49:13.940 --> 00:49:17.370
like almost anything is
a potential embarrassment

00:49:17.370 --> 00:49:18.670
when you're that age.

00:49:18.670 --> 00:49:19.970
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Well, yeah.

00:49:19.970 --> 00:49:21.670
And it's a sport all about
your body, and I was in it

00:49:21.670 --> 00:49:24.280
through my entire childhood,
so my body was changing

00:49:24.280 --> 00:49:26.910
and growing, and I was having
to experience that while

00:49:26.910 --> 00:49:29.320
in like a skintight
dress with no underwear

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:30.760
on because skaters aren't
allowed to wear underwear

00:49:30.760 --> 00:49:33.150
because the judges might
see it, like a line of it.

00:49:33.150 --> 00:49:34.450
And they were like, no, no.

00:49:34.450 --> 00:49:37.900
And, like, having to understand
your body while having an

00:49:37.900 --> 00:49:39.560
audience looking
at it was like --

00:49:39.560 --> 00:49:41.870
but thing is it's
not just skating.

00:49:41.870 --> 00:49:45.230
If you've been in dance, if
you've been in gymnastics,

00:49:45.230 --> 00:49:47.730
I would probably say even
tennis or even a lot of sports,

00:49:47.730 --> 00:49:49.410
there's a lot of that.

00:49:49.410 --> 00:49:52.330
It's, this isn't an
isolated experience.

00:49:52.330 --> 00:49:53.630
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Not at all.

00:49:53.630 --> 00:49:54.930
Not at all.

00:49:54.930 --> 00:49:56.280
But to do it when you're young,
to be, to have, you know,

00:49:56.280 --> 00:49:59.460
you're not even 18, and, yeah.

00:49:59.460 --> 00:50:01.680
And so you go from there.

00:50:01.680 --> 00:50:05.640
So you go from memoir
to fiction, and then--

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:07.060
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I wanted
to perk up a little bit.

00:50:07.060 --> 00:50:08.360
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Did you?

00:50:08.360 --> 00:50:09.660
Okay.

00:50:09.660 --> 00:50:10.960
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah.

00:50:10.960 --> 00:50:12.260
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
[laughs] And so could,

00:50:12.260 --> 00:50:13.560
so this was a web comic.

00:50:13.560 --> 00:50:16.750
This was an Eisner Award
winning web comic was this?

00:50:16.750 --> 00:50:18.620
This is Ignatz Award winning.

00:50:18.620 --> 00:50:19.920
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I don't know.

00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:21.220
I don't remember.

00:50:21.220 --> 00:50:22.520
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: They pile
up, like your skating medals.

00:50:22.520 --> 00:50:23.820
At 1 point, you say that
you have an unhealthy amount

00:50:23.820 --> 00:50:25.120
of skating medals, right?

00:50:25.120 --> 00:50:26.420
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I threw
them all out, except for 1.

00:50:26.420 --> 00:50:27.720
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Really?

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:29.020
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I had so
many, it was disgusting.

00:50:29.020 --> 00:50:30.320
My door actually broke because
my mom used to hang them

00:50:30.320 --> 00:50:31.620
on my door, and then
my door broke.

00:50:31.620 --> 00:50:33.650
And I was like, this is
like, this is stupid.

00:50:33.650 --> 00:50:34.980
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, and
it came across in the book as,

00:50:34.980 --> 00:50:37.770
like, not like, oh,
look at me, but, like,

00:50:37.770 --> 00:50:39.410
literally weighing
you down with the--

00:50:39.410 --> 00:50:40.710
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah.

00:50:40.710 --> 00:50:42.010
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: What
you've been through.

00:50:42.010 --> 00:50:45.240
So can you talk about, this
book comes out in October.

00:50:45.240 --> 00:50:47.970
I can't recommend
it more highly.

00:50:47.970 --> 00:50:51.840
Can you talk about transitioning
to a work of space fiction?

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:53.140
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah.

00:50:53.140 --> 00:50:54.440
I mean, it was easy.

00:50:54.440 --> 00:50:55.740
It was just like, let me
shut down that part of myself

00:50:55.740 --> 00:50:58.740
that wants to, like, examine
who I am and just tell a story

00:50:58.740 --> 00:51:00.480
about all the fun stuff
that I want to do.

00:51:00.480 --> 00:51:03.730
And I would really like to go
to boarding school in space,

00:51:03.730 --> 00:51:07.670
so [laughter] I started
with that.

00:51:07.670 --> 00:51:10.560
I would also really like to
live on a spaceship with a bunch

00:51:10.560 --> 00:51:12.690
of other queer women
and just, like,

00:51:12.690 --> 00:51:15.210
be a little family
together, so I did that too.

00:51:15.210 --> 00:51:17.190
And that's what the
story is about.

00:51:17.190 --> 00:51:19.930
It's about this girl, Mia, and
these 2 stages in her life --

00:51:19.930 --> 00:51:23.030
1 when she is at boarding school
in space, and falls in love,

00:51:23.030 --> 00:51:26.150
and deals with some
things, including bullying,

00:51:26.150 --> 00:51:29.370
and then her, in her older
life, trying to understand

00:51:29.370 --> 00:51:33.250
who she is not as a student, not
as a girl at boarding school,

00:51:33.250 --> 00:51:36.510
but as a girl who
is now a woman.

00:51:36.510 --> 00:51:39.870
And it's long and fun, and
it's still a web comic.

00:51:39.870 --> 00:51:41.170
It's still for free.

00:51:41.170 --> 00:51:42.470
You can read the
whole thing online

00:51:42.470 --> 00:51:44.280
if you just Google On a Sunbeam.

00:51:44.280 --> 00:51:45.580
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: On a Sunbeam.

00:51:45.580 --> 00:51:46.880
And in October--

00:51:46.880 --> 00:51:48.180
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
Where did you get that?

00:51:48.180 --> 00:51:49.850
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Oh, I have my ways.

00:51:49.850 --> 00:51:53.370
[laughter] I just, you
know, it's the patriarchy.

00:51:53.370 --> 00:51:54.670
It's [inaudible].

00:51:54.670 --> 00:51:58.010
Did I just say that out loud?

00:51:58.010 --> 00:51:59.310
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: You did.

00:51:59.310 --> 00:52:00.610
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah,
I'm sorry about that.

00:52:00.610 --> 00:52:04.610
No, what it is, it's partly that
it's the power of First Second,

00:52:04.610 --> 00:52:08.110
but also the power
of Small Press Expo,

00:52:08.110 --> 00:52:10.550
which will be in 2 weeks again.

00:52:10.550 --> 00:52:14.020
They have helped
make it possible

00:52:14.020 --> 00:52:18.010
to bring Tillie Walden
here as well as the person

00:52:18.010 --> 00:52:20.630
who will follow us
next, Ed Piskor.

00:52:20.630 --> 00:52:21.930
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: You mean Ed?

00:52:21.930 --> 00:52:23.230
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: I mean Ed.

00:52:23.230 --> 00:52:24.530
[laughs]

00:52:24.530 --> 00:52:26.980
But, you know, another thing
is 1 thing you guys both are

00:52:26.980 --> 00:52:32.330
drawing about and writing about
is fear versus fearlessness,

00:52:32.330 --> 00:52:37.370
the fear paralyzing you versus
people who seem like they just,

00:52:37.370 --> 00:52:39.320
they seem able to conquer fear.

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:40.730
And there's so much
that goes into that.

00:52:40.730 --> 00:52:42.740
I mean, you talk about quitting,

00:52:42.740 --> 00:52:44.540
and you thought quitting
would be a big deal.

00:52:44.540 --> 00:52:47.090
You quit skating, and was it
your mom that's like, oh, okay.

00:52:47.090 --> 00:52:48.390
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: It
was not a big deal.

00:52:48.390 --> 00:52:49.690
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Not a big deal.

00:52:49.690 --> 00:52:51.440
Everything you thought --
can you talk, you know,

00:52:51.440 --> 00:52:55.910
in getting across that emotional
state, just very quickly,

00:52:55.910 --> 00:52:58.610
can you talk about
sort of tapping fear

00:52:58.610 --> 00:53:01.300
versus fearlessness
for, in your work?

00:53:01.300 --> 00:53:02.820
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I don't know.

00:53:02.820 --> 00:53:06.240
I don't know if there's
a way to conquer fear.

00:53:06.240 --> 00:53:09.000
I feel like all I can do is
just try and work through it

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.090
and try and understand it.

00:53:12.090 --> 00:53:13.390
That's all I really
know how to do.

00:53:13.390 --> 00:53:14.690
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, yeah.

00:53:14.690 --> 00:53:15.990
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah,

00:53:15.990 --> 00:53:17.630
and the fear will
always be there anyway,

00:53:17.630 --> 00:53:20.110
probably until the end.

00:53:20.110 --> 00:53:22.200
So I don't think
there's a moment

00:53:22.200 --> 00:53:26.500
when you start not being scared
anymore, so you just have

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:28.890
to live with it and be
able to work with it.

00:53:28.890 --> 00:53:30.990
And the good thing
is that it's not us.

00:53:30.990 --> 00:53:32.290
It's our books.

00:53:32.290 --> 00:53:38.140
So we're not directly going
towards, you know, people.

00:53:38.140 --> 00:53:39.650
And we something in between.

00:53:39.650 --> 00:53:41.940
We have the books,
so we're safe.

00:53:41.940 --> 00:53:43.800
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: And it's
our way to process it.

00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:45.100
Art lets us deal with it.

00:53:45.100 --> 00:53:46.400
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Absolutely.

00:53:46.400 --> 00:53:49.240
I just fear, deadlines I think
is what I end up fearing most

00:53:49.240 --> 00:53:51.230
when I'm trying to,
and I really mean that.

00:53:51.230 --> 00:53:54.190
Well, what that leads us to,
speaking of Small Press Expo

00:53:54.190 --> 00:53:57.510
and someone along with Tillie
who will be here in 2 weeks,

00:53:57.510 --> 00:54:03.720
someone who I first met at
Small Press Expo 6, 8 years ago.

00:54:03.720 --> 00:54:06.110
Straight out of Pittsburgh.

00:54:06.110 --> 00:54:11.070
He is a huge fan of Marvel
Comics and that '70's aesthetic.

00:54:11.070 --> 00:54:12.920
He's a huge fan of hip-hop.

00:54:12.920 --> 00:54:14.270
He's a huge fan of
so many things.

00:54:14.270 --> 00:54:17.600
But he's able to put it all
in his art with this sort

00:54:17.600 --> 00:54:20.550
of aesthetic that
only he is doing.

00:54:20.550 --> 00:54:24.370
He's one of the very few, if not
only cartoonists working for one

00:54:24.370 --> 00:54:28.840
of the big 2 who does
the writing, the drawing,

00:54:28.840 --> 00:54:30.140
both the penciling and inking,

00:54:30.140 --> 00:54:33.230
the color separation
from end to end.

00:54:33.230 --> 00:54:35.840
He's a 1-man machine.

00:54:35.840 --> 00:54:39.000
Growing up in Pittsburgh,
he went to the Kubert School

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:42.220
of Art, you know, started
by the great Joe Kubert,

00:54:42.220 --> 00:54:43.520
if you know your stuff.

00:54:43.520 --> 00:54:47.220
He got to know, if you know
Harvey Pekar, American Splendor.

00:54:47.220 --> 00:54:49.960
Ed, at a young age, was
doing that, working with him

00:54:49.960 --> 00:54:54.330
on Macedonia, and The Beats, and
American Splendor [inaudible].

00:54:54.330 --> 00:54:56.600
And so then, he went
to Wizzywig,

00:54:56.600 --> 00:54:59.570
which was an Eisner nominee.

00:54:59.570 --> 00:55:02.250
Then, he did Hip Hop
Family Tree, and this is,

00:55:02.250 --> 00:55:04.860
we'll get into how this
is a work that, you know,

00:55:04.860 --> 00:55:06.920
you either have credibility,
you have cred

00:55:06.920 --> 00:55:08.570
with the hip-hop
heads or you don't.

00:55:08.570 --> 00:55:10.740
And he got mad cred for that.

00:55:10.740 --> 00:55:15.000
And so what's coming up now
is he's been working on X-Men:

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.470
Grand Design, and Marvel just
threw him the sandbox and said,

00:55:18.470 --> 00:55:19.880
do what you want to do.

00:55:19.880 --> 00:55:22.900
And so we're going to
have 2 Eisner winners

00:55:22.900 --> 00:55:24.200
up here at 1 time.

00:55:24.200 --> 00:55:25.830
Please welcome Eddie
P. [applause]

00:55:25.830 --> 00:55:28.210
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
Should we move over?

00:55:28.210 --> 00:55:36.650
I think he needs this --
Ed, you need his microphone.

00:55:36.650 --> 00:55:37.950
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

00:55:37.950 --> 00:55:40.470
And while he's doing that, some
of the praise for X-Men so far,

00:55:40.470 --> 00:55:44.870
it's been called a love
letter to that era in comics,

00:55:44.870 --> 00:55:48.110
and it's been called the
intricate labor of love.

00:55:48.110 --> 00:55:51.780
And it's just, it's beautifully,
it's done with such depth,

00:55:51.780 --> 00:55:56.420
and you're able to get, capture
that old Marvel aesthetic,

00:55:56.420 --> 00:55:58.810
and it's a masterpiece, really.

00:55:58.810 --> 00:56:00.110
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I agree.

00:56:00.110 --> 00:56:02.140
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So, yeah.

00:56:02.140 --> 00:56:06.220
[laughter] So 1 thing I want to
ask you guys about is, you know,

00:56:06.220 --> 00:56:09.760
it's, to different degrees,
you're working with editors,

00:56:09.760 --> 00:56:12.310
but when you're telling
personal stories,

00:56:12.310 --> 00:56:14.240
you need certain
amount of freedom.

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:16.340
Do you feel like once
you have a vision,

00:56:16.340 --> 00:56:19.110
do you feel like you're
able to sort of push back

00:56:19.110 --> 00:56:22.410
against editors, or convince
them, or be persuasive and say,

00:56:22.410 --> 00:56:24.120
here's the vision I have?

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:25.840
And are there ways to do

00:56:25.840 --> 00:56:29.060
that where they respect
you creatively?

00:56:29.060 --> 00:56:30.400
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: There are ways

00:56:30.400 --> 00:56:32.150
that they respect
you creatively,

00:56:32.150 --> 00:56:36.790
and by way of Hip Hop Family
Tree being a New York Times best

00:56:36.790 --> 00:56:40.900
seller, [laughter]
they seem to trust

00:56:40.900 --> 00:56:43.420
that I'll be able
to sell them books.

00:56:43.420 --> 00:56:47.300
You know, like when it comes to
that realm of corporate comics,

00:56:47.300 --> 00:56:48.770
which I'm not really
familiar with --

00:56:48.770 --> 00:56:52.720
I'm just kind of visiting
-- it's all about the money.

00:56:52.720 --> 00:56:56.400
So, like, the things that I'm
doing are not so controversial

00:56:56.400 --> 00:57:01.290
that they really, I really need
much of their input or whatever.

00:57:01.290 --> 00:57:05.740
And to some extent, in that
universe, I am a little bit

00:57:05.740 --> 00:57:07.110
of a prima donna where--

00:57:07.110 --> 00:57:08.410
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Are you?

00:57:08.410 --> 00:57:09.710
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I would
like to just work

00:57:09.710 --> 00:57:11.630
on my own stuff in
a lot of ways.

00:57:11.630 --> 00:57:15.110
So, you know, if they
push back too much,

00:57:15.110 --> 00:57:16.830
then I'll just go back
and do my own thing.

00:57:16.830 --> 00:57:18.130
You know what I mean?

00:57:18.130 --> 00:57:19.920
Do Hip Hop Family Tree,
Volume 5 or something.

00:57:19.920 --> 00:57:21.760
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:23.320
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden:
Yeah, I don't know.

00:57:23.320 --> 00:57:26.180
I feel like my editors know
a lot more than me at times.

00:57:26.180 --> 00:57:27.480
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Really?

00:57:27.480 --> 00:57:28.780
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah.

00:57:28.780 --> 00:57:30.080
I'm very much like, after I do
the first draft, and they, like,

00:57:30.080 --> 00:57:31.620
look at a scene, and they're
like, uh-uh, I'm like, okay,

00:57:31.620 --> 00:57:32.920
you're probably right.

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:34.220
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So you're
saying you're not a prima donna?

00:57:34.220 --> 00:57:35.520
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I guess not.

00:57:35.520 --> 00:57:39.700
I guess I just, I know that
I'm so biased, I can't look

00:57:39.700 --> 00:57:41.140
at my work critically at all.

00:57:41.140 --> 00:57:43.190
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So,
yeah, you rely on someone

00:57:43.190 --> 00:57:44.490
with critical distance to say--

00:57:44.490 --> 00:57:45.790
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: I do.

00:57:45.790 --> 00:57:47.090
I do, yeah.

00:57:47.090 --> 00:57:48.390
I have to.

00:57:48.390 --> 00:57:49.690
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:57:49.690 --> 00:57:50.990
And Penelope?

00:57:50.990 --> 00:57:52.290
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Oh, yeah.

00:57:52.290 --> 00:57:53.590
Totally relying on my editor.

00:57:53.590 --> 00:57:54.890
I give him half of my brain
when I begin the book.

00:57:54.890 --> 00:57:56.190
He knows where I'm going, and
at some point, he knows better

00:57:56.190 --> 00:57:57.490
than I do because he
remembers my original idea

00:57:57.490 --> 00:57:58.790
where I'm totally lost

00:57:58.790 --> 00:58:00.950
and confused along the
way, and he's like, focus.

00:58:00.950 --> 00:58:02.390
Remember. I'm like,
okay, thanks.

00:58:02.390 --> 00:58:03.910
So, yeah. Totally need him too.

00:58:03.910 --> 00:58:05.210
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:58:05.210 --> 00:58:08.700
You know, to me, often, there's,
there has to be 1 point where,

00:58:08.700 --> 00:58:10.970
you know, you just feel

00:58:10.970 --> 00:58:13.740
like when you're writing,
you trust your voice.

00:58:13.740 --> 00:58:15.300
You know your voice.

00:58:15.300 --> 00:58:17.500
Have all 3 of you
gotten to places

00:58:17.500 --> 00:58:18.820
where you know your voice?

00:58:18.820 --> 00:58:21.870
You know, because we all
have, we're influenced

00:58:21.870 --> 00:58:23.790
by different writers
and artists early on,

00:58:23.790 --> 00:58:25.600
but then you learn to trust.

00:58:25.600 --> 00:58:27.860
Something inside
gradually emerges.

00:58:27.860 --> 00:58:29.890
You feel like you all have
reached a place where you just,

00:58:29.890 --> 00:58:32.560
your voice is your voice
and you are very comfortable

00:58:32.560 --> 00:58:33.860
in that place?

00:58:33.860 --> 00:58:35.160
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah.

00:58:35.160 --> 00:58:36.460
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah?

00:58:36.460 --> 00:58:37.760
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu: Yeah.

00:58:37.760 --> 00:58:39.060
&gt;&gt; Tillie Walden: Yeah, I do.

00:58:39.060 --> 00:58:40.360
&gt;&gt; Penelope Bagieu:
At least, yeah.

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:41.660
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Took me
a really long time.

00:58:41.660 --> 00:58:42.960
I think I was like 27, already
in the game for like 6 years

00:58:42.960 --> 00:58:44.280
when I finally accepted
who I was.

00:58:44.280 --> 00:58:46.970
You know, I was always trying
to make comics like this or like

00:58:46.970 --> 00:58:50.330
that because there was no
empirical data that the things

00:58:50.330 --> 00:58:54.000
that I like, my taste levels
would resonate on the shelves

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:55.330
because I had nothing
to point to.

00:58:55.330 --> 00:59:00.030
So it took a lot of trust in
myself to get to that level.

00:59:00.030 --> 00:59:02.540
It took a while.

00:59:02.540 --> 00:59:03.840
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
But you're there.

00:59:03.840 --> 00:59:05.140
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I guess.

00:59:05.140 --> 00:59:06.440
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

00:59:06.440 --> 00:59:07.740
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Never satisfied.

00:59:07.740 --> 00:59:09.040
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

00:59:09.040 --> 00:59:10.340
Well, since you're
not satisfied,

00:59:10.340 --> 00:59:11.640
you have to stay with us.

00:59:11.640 --> 00:59:12.940
You have to stay after
class, begin recess.

00:59:12.940 --> 00:59:14.740
But you guys, thank you so much.

00:59:14.740 --> 00:59:18.510
Tillie, Penelope, please
give them a big hand.

00:59:18.510 --> 00:59:29.550
[ Applause ]

00:59:29.550 --> 00:59:31.540
Okay. All right.

00:59:31.540 --> 00:59:33.640
There he is.

00:59:33.640 --> 00:59:35.760
There he is.

00:59:35.760 --> 00:59:37.710
Man, this book is beautiful.

00:59:37.710 --> 00:59:39.800
This is just a -- you know,
I'm going to take a minute.

00:59:39.800 --> 00:59:43.240
I'm going to find this book
because -- and you've got a,

00:59:43.240 --> 00:59:45.840
you had a new one
just drop, right?

00:59:45.840 --> 00:59:47.140
A new X-Men?

00:59:47.140 --> 00:59:48.440
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: New issue
just dropped, and the,

00:59:48.440 --> 00:59:52.200
like the second big book will
come out at the end of October.

00:59:52.200 --> 00:59:53.500
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

00:59:53.500 --> 00:59:55.040
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: That was
the cool thing too, like,

00:59:55.040 --> 00:59:57.710
dealing with Marvel, like,

00:59:57.710 --> 01:00:00.790
they accepted the format
changes I wanted to make.

01:00:00.790 --> 01:00:03.730
Generally speaking, all the
Marvel books are of a piece.

01:00:03.730 --> 01:00:05.030
They look the same.

01:00:05.030 --> 01:00:08.370
They fit next to each
other on the bookshelf.

01:00:08.370 --> 01:00:10.300
But my ego doesn't
work that way,

01:00:10.300 --> 01:00:13.850
so I wanted the book
to be big and giant.

01:00:13.850 --> 01:00:16.380
And if they were going to
use my full superpowers,

01:00:16.380 --> 01:00:18.690
they have to let me design it,

01:00:18.690 --> 01:00:21.210
so they were accepting
of that too.

01:00:21.210 --> 01:00:22.530
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Tell me,
you know, we talked a bit

01:00:22.530 --> 01:00:24.270
about this, but how
does this happen?

01:00:24.270 --> 01:00:27.480
I mean, this is Marvel, and
for them, it's one thing

01:00:27.480 --> 01:00:30.400
to hire a writer to,
or an artist and say,

01:00:30.400 --> 01:00:31.770
hey, we like your stuff.

01:00:31.770 --> 01:00:36.540
You want a shot at writing a
limited run on x, so to speak?

01:00:36.540 --> 01:00:39.290
But to say, we're going
to let you really play

01:00:39.290 --> 01:00:43.510
in a huge sandbox and trust
you to go to town, I mean,

01:00:43.510 --> 01:00:45.380
it's, that's a rare thing.

01:00:45.380 --> 01:00:47.820
How does that happen?

01:00:49.200 --> 01:00:51.620
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: When I got
the Eisner Award for,

01:00:51.620 --> 01:00:54.780
I think it was the second
volume of Hip Hop Family Tree,

01:00:54.780 --> 01:00:59.810
and you're there at the
event, they call your name,

01:00:59.810 --> 01:01:04.370
and as I was walking up, I
didn't quite feel the feeling

01:01:04.370 --> 01:01:07.250
of satisfaction I've been
searching for my entire life

01:01:07.250 --> 01:01:08.670
in this game, and I didn't want

01:01:08.670 --> 01:01:10.840
to do Hip Hop Family
Tree anymore, actually.

01:01:10.840 --> 01:01:13.430
I had about 10 pages to
go on the fourth volume,

01:01:13.430 --> 01:01:16.240
and I got up there and accept
my award, and I'm like,

01:01:16.240 --> 01:01:18.550
this didn't give me what
I, this trophy's hollow.

01:01:18.550 --> 01:01:20.650
You know what I'm saying?

01:01:20.650 --> 01:01:21.950
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: The
ultimate metaphor.

01:01:21.950 --> 01:01:23.250
You hoist it at the event.

01:01:23.250 --> 01:01:24.930
You haven't even left the
San Diego Comic-Con Hall,

01:01:24.930 --> 01:01:26.230
and you feel hollow.

01:01:26.230 --> 01:01:27.530
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Totally.

01:01:27.530 --> 01:01:28.830
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

01:01:28.830 --> 01:01:30.130
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: So I
put a tweet out there.

01:01:30.130 --> 01:01:33.110
I drew just for pleasure for,
like, the first time in years,

01:01:33.110 --> 01:01:35.940
and I decided to draw
this elaborate picture

01:01:35.940 --> 01:01:38.660
of the X-Men because, like,
as a kid, I liked the comic

01:01:38.660 --> 01:01:42.160
or whatever, and I've been
so far away from those kinds

01:01:42.160 --> 01:01:48.410
of comics, I decided just
draw this thing for fun

01:01:48.410 --> 01:01:49.840
since I developed some skills.

01:01:49.840 --> 01:01:51.580
I have never drawn any
of that superhero stuff.

01:01:51.580 --> 01:01:52.910
And it was a lot of fun.

01:01:52.910 --> 01:01:55.030
Put a tweet out into
the universe and said,

01:01:55.030 --> 01:01:56.790
Marvel should just let
me make whatever kind

01:01:56.790 --> 01:01:59.810
of X-Men comic I feel like
making, just like that.

01:01:59.810 --> 01:02:01.440
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So you
weren't even tweeting at Marvel.

01:02:01.440 --> 01:02:03.000
You were just tweeting
to the universe,

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:04.440
so to speak, the
Marvel universe.

01:02:04.440 --> 01:02:06.560
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, because I
never thought about doing work

01:02:06.560 --> 01:02:07.880
for Marvel in any way.

01:02:07.880 --> 01:02:10.800
Like, as a cartoonist,
you make comic books.

01:02:10.800 --> 01:02:12.100
Like, you don't need
to be paired

01:02:12.100 --> 01:02:14.240
up with a writer or artist.

01:02:14.240 --> 01:02:15.540
You know, like--

01:02:15.540 --> 01:02:16.840
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: You do it all.

01:02:16.840 --> 01:02:18.140
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Just, yeah.

01:02:18.140 --> 01:02:19.440
So I make comic books.

01:02:19.440 --> 01:02:20.740
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: So how long
did it take to hear from Marvel?

01:02:20.740 --> 01:02:22.040
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Like an hour.

01:02:22.040 --> 01:02:23.340
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Wow.

01:02:23.340 --> 01:02:24.640
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, yeah.

01:02:24.640 --> 01:02:25.940
It was pretty cool.

01:02:25.940 --> 01:02:27.240
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
The game has changed.

01:02:27.240 --> 01:02:28.540
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah,
it was pretty cool,

01:02:28.540 --> 01:02:29.840
and I let them know that, you
know, this is what I would do.

01:02:29.840 --> 01:02:33.260
The X-Men, for those who don't
know, it's a very sprawling,

01:02:33.260 --> 01:02:35.250
kind of convoluted narrative.

01:02:35.250 --> 01:02:38.830
It goes all over the place,
and there's a lot of confusion

01:02:38.830 --> 01:02:41.030
in those comics,
which is actually kind

01:02:41.030 --> 01:02:42.800
of like what I liked
about it when I was a kid,

01:02:42.800 --> 01:02:47.060
but it takes a lot of work
to parse through all of that.

01:02:47.060 --> 01:02:49.680
So my idea was to take, you
know, the first 30 years

01:02:49.680 --> 01:02:51.040
of those comics --
that's the stuff

01:02:51.040 --> 01:02:52.450
that I liked when I was a boy--

01:02:52.450 --> 01:02:53.750
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:02:53.750 --> 01:02:55.050
This is Chris Claremont
stuff, right?

01:02:55.050 --> 01:02:56.350
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, the
Chris Claremont era.

01:02:56.350 --> 01:02:57.650
And when he left the--

01:02:57.650 --> 01:02:58.950
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
X-Men fans here?

01:02:58.950 --> 01:03:00.250
Any fans of -- yes.

01:03:00.250 --> 01:03:01.550
Nice.

01:03:01.550 --> 01:03:02.850
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Whoa, way
more than I thought.

01:03:02.850 --> 01:03:04.150
That's awesome.

01:03:04.150 --> 01:03:05.450
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:03:05.450 --> 01:03:06.750
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: When he left
the series, I left the series

01:03:06.750 --> 01:03:08.050
and graduated to, you know,

01:03:08.050 --> 01:03:09.780
Fantagraphics and
stuff like that.

01:03:09.780 --> 01:03:12.850
So they liked the idea,
and I'm quite sure

01:03:12.850 --> 01:03:15.660
that they would've liked me
to have done it, you know,

01:03:15.660 --> 01:03:18.450
inside of a year or
something, but 240 pages,

01:03:18.450 --> 01:03:21.770
doing the whole kit and
caboodle, it takes a while, man.

01:03:21.770 --> 01:03:23.230
So it's 3 years.

01:03:23.230 --> 01:03:26.260
I'm good for like 80
to 90 pages a year.

01:03:26.260 --> 01:03:27.560
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
You know your rate.

01:03:27.560 --> 01:03:28.860
You know how to pace.

01:03:28.860 --> 01:03:30.160
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah.

01:03:30.160 --> 01:03:31.460
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
You know how to pace.

01:03:31.460 --> 01:03:32.760
Well, let's talk about
Hip Hop Family Tree.

01:03:32.760 --> 01:03:34.770
I mean, this is just
from Fantagraphics.

01:03:34.770 --> 01:03:38.330
It's, you know, it's just
gorgeous, but also, like,

01:03:38.330 --> 01:03:42.600
I have a Post colleague,
Washington Post colleague

01:03:42.600 --> 01:03:45.140
who is working on a big
hip-hop book now that came

01:03:45.140 --> 01:03:49.480
out of an article, and whenever,
you know, hip-hop is still,

01:03:49.480 --> 01:03:51.800
people are so passionate about
it, and even though it's been

01:03:51.800 --> 01:03:55.690
around for so many decades, so
many aspects of it feel so fresh

01:03:55.690 --> 01:03:59.230
to people that they, you
really can't get it wrong.

01:03:59.230 --> 01:04:00.950
If you get anything
a little bit wrong,

01:04:00.950 --> 01:04:02.280
you're going to hear from it.

01:04:02.280 --> 01:04:05.450
So credibility is
everything, just starting out.

01:04:05.450 --> 01:04:08.320
And so you had to
really do your homework.

01:04:08.320 --> 01:04:11.260
I mean, you can't
just wiki that.

01:04:11.260 --> 01:04:12.560
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: No.

01:04:12.560 --> 01:04:14.150
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: You really
-- can you talk about, this is,

01:04:14.150 --> 01:04:17.630
just from a research standpoint,
was a mammoth undertaking.

01:04:17.630 --> 01:04:19.270
Can you talk about doing that?

01:04:19.270 --> 01:04:20.570
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, for sure.

01:04:20.570 --> 01:04:22.070
I mean, with both
of these projects,

01:04:22.070 --> 01:04:24.040
there's just all
this back-end work

01:04:24.040 --> 01:04:27.480
that doesn't get
seen on the page.

01:04:27.480 --> 01:04:28.780
And with--

01:04:28.780 --> 01:04:30.080
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: All
behind the curtains.

01:04:30.080 --> 01:04:31.650
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yep, and with Hip
Hop Family Tree, you're right.

01:04:31.650 --> 01:04:33.460
You have to have
some credibility,

01:04:33.460 --> 01:04:34.950
and it has to feel organic.

01:04:34.950 --> 01:04:36.420
It has to feel authentic, man.

01:04:36.420 --> 01:04:40.280
Like, that phony
stuff will not fly.

01:04:40.280 --> 01:04:44.750
So my kind of solution to that
with Hip Hop Family Tree was

01:04:44.750 --> 01:04:48.820
to kind of dull the
strips out online first

01:04:48.820 --> 01:04:52.810
to just have even a
fresh set of eyes.

01:04:52.810 --> 01:04:57.000
Like, you know as well as I do
that the anonymous commenter

01:04:57.000 --> 01:04:59.320
on the internet is
very quick and happy

01:04:59.320 --> 01:05:03.170
to let you know if/when
you got something wrong.

01:05:03.170 --> 01:05:06.010
I'm very happy to say that
that just has never come up in,

01:05:06.010 --> 01:05:08.200
like, in the comments on--

01:05:08.200 --> 01:05:09.500
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
That's amazing,

01:05:09.500 --> 01:05:10.800
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Online
because I really did try

01:05:10.800 --> 01:05:13.190
to make my research as
bulletproof as possible.

01:05:13.190 --> 01:05:18.580
And when we first met, you
brought up the word, like,

01:05:18.580 --> 01:05:21.510
"journalism" and using
a journalist process.

01:05:21.510 --> 01:05:22.810
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: You're
doing comics journalism.

01:05:22.810 --> 01:05:24.110
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: And I never
thought of it as that.

01:05:24.110 --> 01:05:28.350
I just didn't, I just wanted
to have artillery in the pocket

01:05:28.350 --> 01:05:31.730
in case somebody said something
weird, and then I could just,

01:05:31.730 --> 01:05:35.370
like, present the materials that
I used to put my comic together.

01:05:35.370 --> 01:05:36.670
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Well, here's the thing.

01:05:36.670 --> 01:05:38.490
I mean, and we know
beefs are still happening

01:05:38.490 --> 01:05:40.890
about who gets credit
for what, right.

01:05:40.890 --> 01:05:44.470
I mean, we can't seem to resolve
[inaudible] Marvel Comics what

01:05:44.470 --> 01:05:49.730
Stan Lee gets credit for versus
Jack Kirby versus Steve Ditko,

01:05:49.730 --> 01:05:53.200
or Gene Cullen [phonetic], or
Marie Severin, who just died.

01:05:53.200 --> 01:05:54.500
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah,
rest in peace.

01:05:54.500 --> 01:05:55.800
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: May
she rest in peace.

01:05:55.800 --> 01:05:57.100
She was legend, and
she was there.

01:05:57.100 --> 01:05:59.290
She worked her way up
from colorist all the way

01:05:59.290 --> 01:06:01.120
up to co-creating Spider-Woman.

01:06:01.120 --> 01:06:04.080
Or, you know, we just
lost Marvel editor

01:06:04.080 --> 01:06:07.550
and creator Gary Friedrich,
who co-created Ghost Rider.

01:06:07.550 --> 01:06:10.220
So if you can't parse
that out in a,

01:06:10.220 --> 01:06:13.940
in the Marvel method system,
hip-hop trying to parse

01:06:13.940 --> 01:06:16.990
out who gets credit for
what beat and doing what

01:06:16.990 --> 01:06:19.020
when they're all in
that creative caldron

01:06:19.020 --> 01:06:20.620
at the beginning, and you

01:06:20.620 --> 01:06:22.000
in some ways are
having to officiate.

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:23.630
You're kind of, drawing
that is kind

01:06:23.630 --> 01:06:25.390
of refereeing that a little bit.

01:06:25.390 --> 01:06:27.270
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, but I
hedge my bets in ways too.

01:06:27.270 --> 01:06:29.250
So like in that first
hip-hop book,

01:06:29.250 --> 01:06:32.180
I believe there are no
less than 3 or 4 guys

01:06:32.180 --> 01:06:35.860
who I allow the space to
claim the creator of--

01:06:35.860 --> 01:06:37.160
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Nice.

01:06:37.160 --> 01:06:38.460
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Hip-hop.

01:06:38.460 --> 01:06:39.760
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And
then, did you ever hear

01:06:39.760 --> 01:06:41.060
from one or the other?

01:06:41.060 --> 01:06:42.360
Like, hey, that's not my take.

01:06:42.360 --> 01:06:43.660
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Sure, yeah.

01:06:43.660 --> 01:06:48.090
Like, after the first volume,
which was largely constructed

01:06:48.090 --> 01:06:52.640
from found materials, that's
when I started to get the calls

01:06:52.640 --> 01:06:56.570
about just like, okay, when
you start to cover me, like,

01:06:56.570 --> 01:07:00.450
let's talk, and then, you know,
I'll give you the full story.

01:07:00.450 --> 01:07:04.460
But the way that hip-hop works,
so you have your, you know,

01:07:04.460 --> 01:07:07.710
Malcolm Gladwell, 10,000
hours in interviewing.

01:07:07.710 --> 01:07:12.720
I don't. So these guys were
trying to run all over me,

01:07:12.720 --> 01:07:16.000
and the way hip-hop works, you
have to puff your chest out,

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:17.320
and you have to take command,

01:07:17.320 --> 01:07:18.700
and you have to be
the alpha dog.

01:07:18.700 --> 01:07:21.420
And I just know that I
was being told fictions.

01:07:21.420 --> 01:07:24.800
And I would just say, like,
man, that's a wild story.

01:07:24.800 --> 01:07:26.340
I love it.

01:07:26.340 --> 01:07:28.430
Is there anybody
else on this planet

01:07:28.430 --> 01:07:30.430
who could corroborate
what you just told me?

01:07:30.430 --> 01:07:31.730
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Yeah, second stories.

01:07:31.730 --> 01:07:33.030
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Anybody else, man.

01:07:33.030 --> 01:07:34.980
And it would always
come back sort of, no.

01:07:34.980 --> 01:07:36.280
Oh, you don't believe me.

01:07:36.280 --> 01:07:37.730
And it's just like, it
was pretty wild, man.

01:07:37.730 --> 01:07:39.030
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:07:39.030 --> 01:07:40.330
So you're getting fake news.

01:07:40.330 --> 01:07:41.630
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Fake news.

01:07:41.630 --> 01:07:42.930
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

01:07:42.930 --> 01:07:44.230
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah,
before it was trendy.

01:07:44.230 --> 01:07:45.530
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: [laughs]
Well, can you talk about it?

01:07:45.530 --> 01:07:47.460
I mean, you ended up, you're
either going to hear back,

01:07:47.460 --> 01:07:50.130
you're going to hear back one
way or the other, and not just

01:07:50.130 --> 01:07:51.650
from anonymous commenters.

01:07:51.650 --> 01:07:53.450
You're going to hear back
maybe from an Ice Cube,

01:07:53.450 --> 01:07:55.410
maybe from a Grandmaster Flash.

01:07:55.410 --> 01:07:56.710
Can you talk about what it was

01:07:56.710 --> 01:08:00.280
like to have certain
people really who were there

01:08:00.280 --> 01:08:01.820
in the closer [inaudible]
at the beginning

01:08:01.820 --> 01:08:04.470
or who were really big
and say, you got it?

01:08:04.470 --> 01:08:07.470
Or just even offhandedly,
go look at this.

01:08:07.470 --> 01:08:08.770
What was that like?

01:08:08.770 --> 01:08:10.660
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Oh,
it was incredible.

01:08:10.660 --> 01:08:12.990
You know, I operate in a vacuum.

01:08:12.990 --> 01:08:16.050
I don't work closely with any
editors or anything like that.

01:08:16.050 --> 01:08:18.110
My entire process has
always been just sit down,

01:08:18.110 --> 01:08:21.670
make the comic, see which
publisher likes it the best,

01:08:21.670 --> 01:08:24.350
and then move forward
from there.

01:08:24.350 --> 01:08:26.620
So putting the strips
out online,

01:08:26.620 --> 01:08:30.070
it became a really fun game
almost week in, week out,

01:08:30.070 --> 01:08:33.170
where I would just kind of
look online and see, oh,

01:08:33.170 --> 01:08:36.810
so this famous rapper
tweeted the comic or that.

01:08:36.810 --> 01:08:40.900
I mean, the success of
the series is really in,

01:08:40.900 --> 01:08:43.530
thanks in great part
to the kind of word

01:08:43.530 --> 01:08:46.260
of mouth that, you
know, Ice Cube--

01:08:46.260 --> 01:08:47.560
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: What's,
yeah, I was going to --

01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:49.490
what's one of the coolest
things you saw that was like,

01:08:49.490 --> 01:08:51.490
whoa, okay, so-and-so--

01:08:51.490 --> 01:08:53.500
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, well,
this photo right here, man,

01:08:53.500 --> 01:08:55.700
this is Fab 5 Freddy,
the host of Yo!

01:08:55.700 --> 01:08:59.040
MTV Raps from when,
you know, I was a kid.

01:08:59.040 --> 01:09:01.780
Like, you know, when, I
didn't take this photo.

01:09:01.780 --> 01:09:03.080
You know what I mean?

01:09:03.080 --> 01:09:05.270
This was just something that
was online that, you know,

01:09:05.270 --> 01:09:07.110
I was tagged in on Twitter
or something like that.

01:09:07.110 --> 01:09:08.870
So when I see things like
this, it blows my mind.

01:09:08.870 --> 01:09:12.600
The most popular strip was
definitely this one that I did

01:09:12.600 --> 01:09:18.170
about how Ice Cube met Dr.
Dre at like a backyard cookout

01:09:18.170 --> 01:09:21.500
in the super early '80's.

01:09:21.500 --> 01:09:26.040
And when Ice Cube
spread the strip out like

01:09:26.040 --> 01:09:28.480
on his social media
platforms, you know, his people

01:09:28.480 --> 01:09:31.640
or whatever, he took
ownership of it.

01:09:31.640 --> 01:09:34.610
So he said, hey, read this
comic about when I met Dre.

01:09:34.610 --> 01:09:37.930
So it wasn't like,
look at this bullshit.

01:09:37.930 --> 01:09:39.390
You know, pardon my French.

01:09:39.390 --> 01:09:41.400
It was like, yeah, this is,

01:09:41.400 --> 01:09:42.880
check out this comic
about when I met Dre.

01:09:42.880 --> 01:09:44.790
And it just, it spread
like wildfire.

01:09:44.790 --> 01:09:46.300
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, and
that's the kind of thing,

01:09:46.300 --> 01:09:48.640
the kind of recommendation
like when you say to a friend,

01:09:48.640 --> 01:09:50.710
you know, that isn't, you
don't need a hype man.

01:09:50.710 --> 01:09:53.310
That's just a friend saying to
a friend, check this out, which,

01:09:53.310 --> 01:09:56.500
in a way, has a lot more, you
know, a lot more influence.

01:09:56.500 --> 01:09:57.800
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Never took
it for granted, man.

01:09:57.800 --> 01:09:59.100
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, yeah.

01:09:59.100 --> 01:10:00.400
That's the way to do it.

01:10:00.400 --> 01:10:01.700
So look at that.

01:10:01.700 --> 01:10:03.000
And look at, now, am I wrong?

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:04.300
You know, so you're
nodding to Marvel.

01:10:04.300 --> 01:10:06.250
Is that a little bit of
like a Kirby crackle there,

01:10:06.250 --> 01:10:07.890
a little nod to Jack Kirby?

01:10:07.890 --> 01:10:09.190
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Oh, for sure.

01:10:09.190 --> 01:10:11.580
At any moment, like, I
wanted this comic to look

01:10:11.580 --> 01:10:15.450
like it was ripped from that
time period that I was covered,

01:10:15.450 --> 01:10:18.910
so it's like late '70's, early
'80's, and try to capture

01:10:18.910 --> 01:10:20.880
that aesthetic as
much as possible.

01:10:20.880 --> 01:10:22.180
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:10:22.180 --> 01:10:23.480
And you even captured, like,
you didn't want to do it

01:10:23.480 --> 01:10:24.780
on a slick white paper.

01:10:24.780 --> 01:10:27.210
You wanted that sort
of tan, weathered,

01:10:27.210 --> 01:10:30.050
6-month old comic
book aesthetic, right?

01:10:30.050 --> 01:10:31.350
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, yeah.

01:10:31.350 --> 01:10:35.670
I just like that look and feel
of a well-read, old comic book.

01:10:35.670 --> 01:10:38.590
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah,
yeah, which, in a way too,

01:10:38.590 --> 01:10:41.670
is great because old
album covers, you know,

01:10:41.670 --> 01:10:43.890
they get a little
weathered, and so part of it,

01:10:43.890 --> 01:10:45.940
you feel like you're, like,
holding a weathered comic book,

01:10:45.940 --> 01:10:49.230
but also, some of these are
so evocative of the time,

01:10:49.230 --> 01:10:51.170
you feel like you're
holding an old album cover.

01:10:51.170 --> 01:10:55.010
People remember vinyl or new
people use, buy vinyl now.

01:10:55.010 --> 01:10:56.550
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Down to
the paper that the,

01:10:56.550 --> 01:11:01.020
those books were printed on was
a design choice that I made.

01:11:01.020 --> 01:11:05.590
Like, I called and got in touch
with several Chinese publishers

01:11:05.590 --> 01:11:08.620
to try to get the
exact perfect paper.

01:11:08.620 --> 01:11:11.190
And the biggest compliment
whenever I'm at a signing

01:11:11.190 --> 01:11:12.790
or anything like that,
when I see people kind

01:11:12.790 --> 01:11:15.100
of like rubbing my books.

01:11:15.100 --> 01:11:19.200
Like, even subconsciously,
it's a big compliment.

01:11:19.200 --> 01:11:22.390
And if we're going to, you know,
chop down trees to make books,

01:11:22.390 --> 01:11:24.740
like, might as well make
very tactile experiences,

01:11:24.740 --> 01:11:27.330
like the most beautiful
books possible.

01:11:27.330 --> 01:11:29.840
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Yeah, and I should,

01:11:29.840 --> 01:11:32.660
reminds me all these
authors will be signing,

01:11:32.660 --> 01:11:34.300
so if you haven't
gone to the, you know,

01:11:34.300 --> 01:11:36.190
you should go to their signing.

01:11:36.190 --> 01:11:37.790
When is your signing,
by the way?

01:11:37.790 --> 01:11:39.390
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I think it's
like five thirty to six thirty.

01:11:39.390 --> 01:11:40.690
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

01:11:40.690 --> 01:11:42.290
So if you go to his signing,
make sure to rub your book,

01:11:42.290 --> 01:11:44.340
and he'll check it out.

01:11:44.340 --> 01:11:45.640
[laughter] So--

01:11:45.640 --> 01:11:47.080
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Well, now, that
would just be pandering now.

01:11:47.080 --> 01:11:48.380
You don't have to.

01:11:48.380 --> 01:11:49.680
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: It would.

01:11:49.680 --> 01:11:52.360
So, but you can see that
weathered aesthetic, but,

01:11:52.360 --> 01:11:55.540
I mean, so can you talk about,
you know, you're evocative

01:11:55.540 --> 01:11:59.910
of Claremont's X-Men and getting
to play with the superheroes?

01:11:59.910 --> 01:12:02.550
And, I mean, you
really, I think,

01:12:02.550 --> 01:12:05.650
it seems like you're
referencing, you might,

01:12:05.650 --> 01:12:09.680
like hundreds of comics
and dozens, and dozens,

01:12:09.680 --> 01:12:11.170
and dozens of characters.

01:12:11.170 --> 01:12:14.690
I mean, you're going deep with
little nods here and there.

01:12:14.690 --> 01:12:17.670
You talk about, it seems
like Hip Hop Family Tree,

01:12:17.670 --> 01:12:20.380
you're really, you're going
deep with the knowledge.

01:12:20.380 --> 01:12:25.180
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, it took
about 8000 pages of material.

01:12:25.180 --> 01:12:27.380
You know, it's 30
years of comics,

01:12:27.380 --> 01:12:30.160
not just from the main series,
but there are tangential series

01:12:30.160 --> 01:12:32.500
and all sorts of
things like that.

01:12:32.500 --> 01:12:34.250
About 8000 pages of material.

01:12:34.250 --> 01:12:39.340
Cull all of that down
into a 240-page story

01:12:39.340 --> 01:12:41.730
with a satisfying beginning,
middle, and ending, you know,

01:12:41.730 --> 01:12:44.690
like not that bait and switch
of cliffhanger at the end.

01:12:44.690 --> 01:12:45.990
Come back next month.

01:12:45.990 --> 01:12:48.190
See how they get
out of that scrape.

01:12:48.190 --> 01:12:50.320
Leave on another cliffhanger.

01:12:50.320 --> 01:12:53.390
So I, when I started
this project, I got,

01:12:53.390 --> 01:12:56.210
I bought the biggest kind

01:12:56.210 --> 01:12:58.980
of bulletin board
that money can buy.

01:12:58.980 --> 01:13:04.660
It's like as big as a school, as
a elementary school chalkboard.

01:13:04.660 --> 01:13:06.970
And I just sort of
put it on its side

01:13:06.970 --> 01:13:08.610
and got all these note cards

01:13:08.610 --> 01:13:10.890
as I was making notes
along the way.

01:13:10.890 --> 01:13:13.900
And, you know, red
yarn string from this

01:13:13.900 --> 01:13:15.560
and pushpin to that one.

01:13:15.560 --> 01:13:16.860
And this very--

01:13:16.860 --> 01:13:19.360
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Almost like
the way you track a mob family.

01:13:19.360 --> 01:13:20.660
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Exactly.

01:13:20.660 --> 01:13:23.200
It, like, it was like, you
know, the Barksdale family tree

01:13:23.200 --> 01:13:25.070
or something like
that in The Wire.

01:13:25.070 --> 01:13:28.560
And, but it would
be these phrases

01:13:28.560 --> 01:13:33.110
that would just sound totally
insane read all by themselves.

01:13:33.110 --> 01:13:35.950
So, like, I was praying that,
you know, I just wouldn't die

01:13:35.950 --> 01:13:37.870
in a car crash or
something like that.

01:13:37.870 --> 01:13:40.400
My parents have to
clean out my house,

01:13:40.400 --> 01:13:44.270
and then they see this bulletin
board full of these notes

01:13:44.270 --> 01:13:45.890
that say something like,

01:13:45.890 --> 01:13:49.090
the shadow king was sexually
transmitted to his son, or,

01:13:49.090 --> 01:13:51.800
and then, like, you know,
my parents might think

01:13:51.800 --> 01:13:53.330
that they dodged a bullet.

01:13:53.330 --> 01:13:55.150
You know, it's like,
oh, it's good.

01:13:55.150 --> 01:13:57.140
It's good he's off the streets.

01:13:57.140 --> 01:13:59.000
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: But then, they
would say, he was a cartoonist,

01:13:59.000 --> 01:14:00.320
and that explains it all.

01:14:00.320 --> 01:14:02.600
You get away with so much when
you're a cartoonist, right.

01:14:02.600 --> 01:14:04.520
Your research material.

01:14:04.520 --> 01:14:06.790
But, I mean, and this
is just gorgeous.

01:14:06.790 --> 01:14:10.100
Do you have a favorite
X-Men artist?

01:14:10.100 --> 01:14:11.400
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I don't.

01:14:11.400 --> 01:14:13.810
Like, they definitely,
they being Marvel,

01:14:13.810 --> 01:14:16.890
definitely hired the
top talent of the day

01:14:16.890 --> 01:14:19.530
to draw their comics
or whatever.

01:14:19.530 --> 01:14:22.100
And, yeah, I, you know,
there's a million of those guys

01:14:22.100 --> 01:14:23.900
that I like, and it's all
for different reasons.

01:14:23.900 --> 01:14:25.200
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, yeah.

01:14:25.200 --> 01:14:28.570
So you were nodding -- so was
there, when it comes to X-Men,

01:14:28.570 --> 01:14:32.900
if you had to bookend certain
years that really influenced you

01:14:32.900 --> 01:14:35.670
and you really were
nodding to more than others,

01:14:35.670 --> 01:14:36.970
what would you say sort of a--

01:14:36.970 --> 01:14:38.990
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: You know, I don't
know what years these things

01:14:38.990 --> 01:14:43.000
came out, but it would be
Issue like say 108 to 137.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:45.730
Late, mid '70's.

01:14:45.730 --> 01:14:47.860
The John Byrne, Chris
Claremont era.

01:14:47.860 --> 01:14:50.360
And that's the, those
are the comics that all

01:14:50.360 --> 01:14:52.560
of these movies kind
of derive from.

01:14:52.560 --> 01:14:56.500
And I kind of think of that the
stuff that Chris Claremont did

01:14:56.500 --> 01:14:59.630
in his early career
on the X-Men,

01:14:59.630 --> 01:15:01.780
he created a pretty
astounding piece

01:15:01.780 --> 01:15:03.720
of kind of modern mythology.

01:15:03.720 --> 01:15:07.940
And part of my take on this
project is the way mythology

01:15:07.940 --> 01:15:11.350
works, it has to be
kind of reinterpreted,

01:15:11.350 --> 01:15:13.520
almost like a sort of
a game of telephone.

01:15:13.520 --> 01:15:19.400
So in a world now where I,
like, just walking here, like,

01:15:19.400 --> 01:15:24.150
I see people with, like,
Avengers shirts on, and, like,

01:15:24.150 --> 01:15:26.580
when I grew up, like, Avengers
was as corny as can be.

01:15:26.580 --> 01:15:29.880
Like, the X-Men were
like the pirates,

01:15:29.880 --> 01:15:32.020
and the Avengers
were like the Navy.

01:15:32.020 --> 01:15:34.030
So I have to--

01:15:34.030 --> 01:15:36.420
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Whoa, hold on.

01:15:36.420 --> 01:15:37.920
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Well,
I'm just saying, like,

01:15:37.920 --> 01:15:40.250
they were just more
punk rock, more outlaw.

01:15:40.250 --> 01:15:41.550
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yes.

01:15:41.550 --> 01:15:42.850
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: So I just have
to remind everybody, like,

01:15:42.850 --> 01:15:44.150
kind of how cool the X-Men are.

01:15:44.150 --> 01:15:45.450
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:15:45.450 --> 01:15:47.290
No, Avengers Assemble
sounded cornier before.

01:15:47.290 --> 01:15:50.550
And are you a fan of the --
I mean, the Avengers, yeah --

01:15:50.550 --> 01:15:53.010
are you a fan of the
X-Men films at all?

01:15:53.010 --> 01:15:54.650
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I've seen them
all, but I kind of, like,

01:15:54.650 --> 01:15:56.460
as soon as I leave the
theater, I forget about it.

01:15:56.460 --> 01:15:58.990
You know, just go there with
friends and kind of hang out.

01:15:58.990 --> 01:16:02.330
I like it at the time, but
I'm not one of those people

01:16:02.330 --> 01:16:05.020
who sees a movie that's
based off of a book,

01:16:05.020 --> 01:16:07.330
and I complain that, like,
oh, they got it wrong.

01:16:07.330 --> 01:16:09.000
Like, it's a different medium.

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:10.800
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, your
childhood wasn't ruined.

01:16:10.800 --> 01:16:13.000
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: That's, and
that's what I say to people,

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:15.110
like the old, kind of
like basement-dwelling,

01:16:15.110 --> 01:16:17.580
neckbeard guys who mess around.

01:16:17.580 --> 01:16:19.240
Like, I'm like, listen, I'm
not coming to your house

01:16:19.240 --> 01:16:20.540
and burning your old comics.

01:16:20.540 --> 01:16:22.290
Like, if you don't like
it, just don't read it.

01:16:22.290 --> 01:16:25.670
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay, so we
apologize if you are in the Navy

01:16:25.670 --> 01:16:27.450
and are a neckbeard guy.

01:16:27.450 --> 01:16:28.810
The twofer.

01:16:28.810 --> 01:16:30.140
We're really--

01:16:30.140 --> 01:16:32.100
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Nah,
the Navy's cool.

01:16:32.100 --> 01:16:37.000
I'm just saying it's, I'm
just saying that it's--

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:39.440
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Not the neckbeard.

01:16:39.440 --> 01:16:40.740
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: You know, square.

01:16:40.740 --> 01:16:42.040
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, yeah.

01:16:42.040 --> 01:16:43.340
[laughter] The, we
talked about you getting,

01:16:43.340 --> 01:16:44.640
I know you don't
need affirmation,

01:16:44.640 --> 01:16:47.330
but getting confirmation
from the hip-hop community,

01:16:47.330 --> 01:16:52.690
from old X-Men guys who
worked on the X-Men books and,

01:16:52.690 --> 01:16:54.820
or anyone else from
the Marvel world.

01:16:54.820 --> 01:16:59.320
Have you gotten sort of
that kind of, I don't know,

01:16:59.320 --> 01:17:02.530
not affirmation, but just
sort of positive reaction?

01:17:02.530 --> 01:17:07.910
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: The answer would
kind of be not no, but just,

01:17:07.910 --> 01:17:09.880
it's just like a baseline.

01:17:09.880 --> 01:17:13.270
Like, I got to spend a lot
of time with Chris Claremont,

01:17:13.270 --> 01:17:16.550
and my approach when
dealing with him --

01:17:16.550 --> 01:17:19.290
now, Chris Claremont
wrote this comic for,

01:17:19.290 --> 01:17:20.950
like, almost 17 years.

01:17:20.950 --> 01:17:23.180
It's his baby.

01:17:23.180 --> 01:17:26.340
So my approach when dealing
with Claremont was almost like,

01:17:26.340 --> 01:17:29.030
I felt like I was kind
of dating his daughter.

01:17:29.030 --> 01:17:32.870
So I just, as a student of this
form, you know, I don't pretend

01:17:32.870 --> 01:17:36.710
to know everything, and I
consider myself to be a student.

01:17:36.710 --> 01:17:38.010
I shut my mouth.

01:17:38.010 --> 01:17:39.310
I opened my ears.

01:17:39.310 --> 01:17:40.640
And I just receive
information, you know.

01:17:40.640 --> 01:17:44.940
So it was, you know,
senpai, kohai kind of thing.

01:17:44.940 --> 01:17:46.240
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:17:46.240 --> 01:17:50.070
And in terms of the artistic,
I mean, how did you approach,

01:17:50.070 --> 01:17:54.040
are there certain ways --
you know, you're so specific.

01:17:54.040 --> 01:17:56.880
You remind me of, like, when I
talk to someone like Chris Ware,

01:17:56.880 --> 01:18:00.790
and if it comes back, if it
ships back from, say, China,

01:18:00.790 --> 01:18:02.660
and just he can see, you know,

01:18:02.660 --> 01:18:06.860
colors just on page
93, building stories.

01:18:06.860 --> 01:18:10.080
Just something, they
didn't quite nail it.

01:18:10.080 --> 01:18:12.930
But now, instead of, like,
working with Fantagraphics,

01:18:12.930 --> 01:18:16.930
working with Marvel, when it
comes to the art, the printing,

01:18:16.930 --> 01:18:20.060
lettering, is there anything
that, does it all feel the same,

01:18:20.060 --> 01:18:22.030
or is there something
you've had to adjust to?

01:18:22.030 --> 01:18:23.870
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: It feels pretty
much the same, but the thing is,

01:18:23.870 --> 01:18:26.750
you know, working with
a Fantagraphics, you're,

01:18:26.750 --> 01:18:29.830
I get to work with the
people who have kind

01:18:29.830 --> 01:18:31.240
of skin the game, so to speak.

01:18:31.240 --> 01:18:33.800
Like, the people who are there,
like, investing their money

01:18:33.800 --> 01:18:38.540
into the product, and they
want this book to be true

01:18:38.540 --> 01:18:41.220
to the vision that
it's supposed to be.

01:18:41.220 --> 01:18:44.130
With Marvel, it's been a
long time since, you know,

01:18:44.130 --> 01:18:45.430
Martin Goodman was there.

01:18:45.430 --> 01:18:48.430
And then, the closest relation
to the originator was Stan Lee,

01:18:48.430 --> 01:18:51.280
and he hasn't been in the mix
for a really long time either.

01:18:51.280 --> 01:18:52.590
So it's all, you know,

01:18:52.590 --> 01:18:56.160
just people who are
going to their job.

01:18:56.160 --> 01:18:57.460
They have a certain
passion for it,

01:18:57.460 --> 01:19:02.760
but you can absolutely tell the
difference that, like, you know,

01:19:02.760 --> 01:19:05.480
Disney money is being spent
on this rather than, like,

01:19:05.480 --> 01:19:09.090
the money from my own
pocket kind of thing.

01:19:09.090 --> 01:19:10.770
That said, the people
that I work

01:19:10.770 --> 01:19:15.360
with there are totally behind me
making the most beautiful books

01:19:15.360 --> 01:19:17.040
that we can.

01:19:17.040 --> 01:19:21.060
So we're able to get, you know,
proof copies way ahead of time

01:19:21.060 --> 01:19:24.000
so that I could adjust
things and, you know,

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:25.660
have a lot of say
in the paper stock.

01:19:25.660 --> 01:19:28.730
Like, all of these kind of
back-end elements to just try

01:19:28.730 --> 01:19:32.580
to make, like, a
really solid unit.

01:19:32.580 --> 01:19:34.190
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
Yeah, absolutely.

01:19:34.190 --> 01:19:37.110
And these covers, and
so to have such control

01:19:37.110 --> 01:19:40.000
over the covers because, you
know, you have top writers

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:41.440
and artists working
for the big 2.

01:19:41.440 --> 01:19:44.250
They don't, they might not
have any say over the cover.

01:19:44.250 --> 01:19:47.830
So the fact that you get
sort of not only, you know,

01:19:47.830 --> 01:19:51.630
beginning to end process and
cover to cover, it's all you.

01:19:51.630 --> 01:19:54.770
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Part of the
idea is to make these,

01:19:54.770 --> 01:19:58.480
this Grand Design thing kind
of the definitive X-Men comic,

01:19:58.480 --> 01:20:01.400
a comic that you can
point to and give somebody

01:20:01.400 --> 01:20:03.480
if they were curious
about the X-Men.

01:20:03.480 --> 01:20:06.000
And now, the comic books
have different covers

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:07.650
than what we're seeing appear.

01:20:07.650 --> 01:20:10.390
And that, those comics
have a different kind

01:20:10.390 --> 01:20:11.690
of distribution mechanism.

01:20:11.690 --> 01:20:13.190
They go to comic shops.

01:20:13.190 --> 01:20:16.610
So the guys at the comic shops,
they want to see cool costumes,

01:20:16.610 --> 01:20:20.140
and, you know, muscles,
and whatever.

01:20:20.140 --> 01:20:26.030
These books are in regular
bookstores, you know,

01:20:26.030 --> 01:20:27.640
at Barnes &amp; Noble or whatever.

01:20:27.640 --> 01:20:31.360
So what I want to communicate
with the covers of the big books

01:20:31.360 --> 01:20:33.400
that have, like, a
wider distribution,

01:20:33.400 --> 01:20:35.410
I need to get the
concept across, like,

01:20:35.410 --> 01:20:39.170
as fast as possible, and that's
the spirit with these things.

01:20:39.170 --> 01:20:43.530
And so it's less about just, you
know, putting, stacking bodies

01:20:43.530 --> 01:20:45.430
and fight scenes or whatever.

01:20:45.430 --> 01:20:49.270
Just communicate the idea in
as quick a fashion as possible.

01:20:49.270 --> 01:20:50.570
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:20:50.570 --> 01:20:54.530
And, you know, Rob Liefeld,
the Deadpool creator, I mean,

01:20:54.530 --> 01:20:57.680
what he called the way you did
is he calls the perfect primer,

01:20:57.680 --> 01:21:00.390
or some people say
"primer," for young and old

01:21:00.390 --> 01:21:01.830
if you want to learn X-Men.

01:21:01.830 --> 01:21:05.950
Do we have anyone here
considers themself young?

01:21:05.950 --> 01:21:07.460
Anyone? Anyone?

01:21:07.460 --> 01:21:08.760
Oh--

01:21:08.760 --> 01:21:10.060
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I see a youngster.

01:21:10.060 --> 01:21:11.360
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: How about old?

01:21:11.360 --> 01:21:12.660
Anyone consider?

01:21:12.660 --> 01:21:13.960
Old, but you--

01:21:13.960 --> 01:21:15.260
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: We got a lot
of middle agers, it seems.

01:21:15.260 --> 01:21:16.560
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, wow.

01:21:16.560 --> 01:21:17.860
That's, so this, no,
this book is so for you.

01:21:17.860 --> 01:21:19.160
It's just beautifully done.

01:21:19.160 --> 01:21:24.310
So, you know, is it, knowing
how you work, you know,

01:21:24.310 --> 01:21:28.420
you're not the type to
sign an Aaron Rodgers deal

01:21:28.420 --> 01:21:30.900
and commit yourself to,
or [inaudible], you know,

01:21:30.900 --> 01:21:32.660
to Marvel for 5 years.

01:21:32.660 --> 01:21:35.570
You're not going to do a James
Bond thing and be locked in.

01:21:35.570 --> 01:21:39.330
What, how far out do you
see going with Grand Design?

01:21:39.330 --> 01:21:41.150
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I'm working
on the last 2 issues.

01:21:41.150 --> 01:21:44.720
It'll take me until next
summer, but, you know, that's,

01:21:44.720 --> 01:21:46.110
this is what I have
to offer them.

01:21:46.110 --> 01:21:47.800
You know, like I try --

01:21:47.800 --> 01:21:50.750
thankfully, the Hip Hop
Family Tree thing really blew

01:21:50.750 --> 01:21:53.210
up in a way that I
could really pick

01:21:53.210 --> 01:21:56.220
and choose what I'm
going to end up doing.

01:21:56.220 --> 01:21:57.700
And this is what I
could offer them.

01:21:57.700 --> 01:22:00.210
This is all that I have
to kind of give them.

01:22:00.210 --> 01:22:02.600
And I have to go back
and just get these ideas

01:22:02.600 --> 01:22:04.300
that I've been having
in my head,

01:22:04.300 --> 01:22:06.020
get them out there on paper.

01:22:06.020 --> 01:22:08.130
This is the example of one
of the comic book covers

01:22:08.130 --> 01:22:10.180
that would be in
the comic shops.

01:22:10.180 --> 01:22:11.590
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna:
That's just beautiful.

01:22:11.590 --> 01:22:15.380
And so that, was that your idea
to kind of have these covers?

01:22:15.380 --> 01:22:16.680
You know, the--

01:22:16.680 --> 01:22:17.980
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: It
actually wasn't.

01:22:17.980 --> 01:22:19.310
Like, that was like a
really great contribution

01:22:19.310 --> 01:22:20.610
of the editor.

01:22:20.610 --> 01:22:24.680
I came up with some ideas that
ended up being variant covers

01:22:24.680 --> 01:22:26.540
or whatever, but when he said,

01:22:26.540 --> 01:22:29.340
what if we do 6 interconnecting
covers that just kind

01:22:29.340 --> 01:22:32.440
of show the whole
tapestry of the--

01:22:32.440 --> 01:22:33.740
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Is this
[inaudible] or somebody else?

01:22:33.740 --> 01:22:35.590
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: It was my direct
editor named Chris Robinson.

01:22:35.590 --> 01:22:36.890
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Okay.

01:22:36.890 --> 01:22:38.190
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Good guy.

01:22:38.190 --> 01:22:39.490
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Shout
out to Chris Robinson.

01:22:39.490 --> 01:22:40.790
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, and
when he came up with

01:22:40.790 --> 01:22:42.250
that idea, it was a bet.

01:22:42.250 --> 01:22:43.730
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: These
are just beautiful.

01:22:43.730 --> 01:22:45.210
Just gorgeous.

01:22:45.210 --> 01:22:46.510
And look at that.

01:22:46.510 --> 01:22:49.410
I mean, that, you know, the
depth of field, by the way,

01:22:49.410 --> 01:22:53.300
you're able to achieve, that,
you know, that's a long time.

01:22:53.300 --> 01:22:54.600
That's--

01:22:54.600 --> 01:22:55.900
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, thanks, man.

01:22:55.900 --> 01:22:57.200
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: That's
decades of skills right there.

01:22:57.200 --> 01:22:58.500
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah,
I guess, man.

01:22:58.500 --> 01:22:59.800
We've known each other
a long time, Mike.

01:22:59.800 --> 01:23:01.100
Goddamn.

01:23:01.100 --> 01:23:02.400
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: [laughs]
You know, like you said,

01:23:02.400 --> 01:23:05.610
been in this game a minute,
and, but look at the texture,

01:23:05.610 --> 01:23:10.180
the feel of the Ben-Day dots,
you know, on there, and--

01:23:10.180 --> 01:23:12.930
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, once again,
doing everything I can to try

01:23:12.930 --> 01:23:14.540
to make it look like
it was a comic ripped

01:23:14.540 --> 01:23:15.880
from that time period.

01:23:15.880 --> 01:23:18.820
Now, this panel would've been
maybe 1 of like 10 panels

01:23:18.820 --> 01:23:21.370
on a page, so that's a
very, very small panel,

01:23:21.370 --> 01:23:23.300
so that's why she looks
like she has measles.

01:23:23.300 --> 01:23:24.600
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:23:24.600 --> 01:23:25.900
[laughter]

01:23:25.900 --> 01:23:27.200
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Because
it was very, very tiny.

01:23:27.200 --> 01:23:28.500
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: You're
approximating the tech

01:23:28.500 --> 01:23:29.800
of the time, you
know, what you had,

01:23:29.800 --> 01:23:31.100
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: It's very
Lichtenstein blown up that way.

01:23:31.100 --> 01:23:33.260
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, and
the classic Snikt Wolverine,

01:23:33.260 --> 01:23:35.140
just even nodding to that.

01:23:35.140 --> 01:23:36.440
I love that.

01:23:36.440 --> 01:23:38.870
When Wolverine was still,
you know, closer to 5 feet

01:23:38.870 --> 01:23:41.580
than 6 feet and low
to the ground.

01:23:41.580 --> 01:23:42.880
Yeah, and look at that.

01:23:42.880 --> 01:23:44.180
Oh, that's just gorgeous.

01:23:44.180 --> 01:23:46.470
A little more Kirby
crackle popping there.

01:23:46.470 --> 01:23:48.200
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, I'm learning
a lot just in terms of, like,

01:23:48.200 --> 01:23:49.500
drawing this, like, action stuff

01:23:49.500 --> 01:23:51.480
that I never even
thought to draw.

01:23:51.480 --> 01:23:56.510
It, everything I do is kind
of just like an education.

01:23:56.510 --> 01:23:59.080
And playing around with
this superhero stuff,

01:23:59.080 --> 01:24:03.390
it's like now I can't really,
like, fake my anatomy as much.

01:24:03.390 --> 01:24:06.510
You know, like I would
be raked over the coals

01:24:06.510 --> 01:24:08.120
by the superhero fans.

01:24:08.120 --> 01:24:10.560
So it's like I'm kind of
learning on the job to try

01:24:10.560 --> 01:24:12.710
to get more dynamic
and whatever,

01:24:12.710 --> 01:24:14.180
for this project, you know.

01:24:14.180 --> 01:24:16.010
Of course, it's required
for this, but--

01:24:16.010 --> 01:24:17.310
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: If
you're going to, like,

01:24:17.310 --> 01:24:18.900
foreshorten an arm and
do something like that,

01:24:18.900 --> 01:24:21.500
you're going to have to
nail it, and, you know,

01:24:21.500 --> 01:24:26.010
Kirby could go bold, but
still had to be true.

01:24:26.010 --> 01:24:27.360
This is just, look at that.

01:24:27.360 --> 01:24:29.310
That's just, that's gorgeous.

01:24:29.310 --> 01:24:31.610
So what is, what's next for you?

01:24:31.610 --> 01:24:36.040
Because I know every project
for you is a project of passion.

01:24:36.040 --> 01:24:37.340
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: It's true.

01:24:37.340 --> 01:24:38.640
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:24:38.640 --> 01:24:39.940
Do you know what's
coming up on, for you?

01:24:39.940 --> 01:24:41.240
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I definitely
do, and there's,

01:24:41.240 --> 01:24:44.550
it's a subject matter that's
really not been covered much

01:24:44.550 --> 01:24:47.490
in -- it's very, there's some
new stuff that's happening

01:24:47.490 --> 01:24:49.700
in our culture, and I
just don't want to say

01:24:49.700 --> 01:24:52.790
because I can't let some
other schmuck beat me to it.

01:24:52.790 --> 01:24:54.090
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: [laughs] Yes.

01:24:54.090 --> 01:24:55.390
Yeah.

01:24:55.390 --> 01:24:56.690
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: But
I do have ideas.

01:24:56.690 --> 01:24:57.990
I have a ton of them.

01:24:57.990 --> 01:24:59.290
I've been taking notes, putting
things together ahead of time,

01:24:59.290 --> 01:25:01.720
so it's like I have
62 more pages to draw.

01:25:01.720 --> 01:25:03.020
I could do 2 pages a week.

01:25:03.020 --> 01:25:05.140
You know, once I
get done with this,

01:25:05.140 --> 01:25:09.030
I'm going to just probably
go to Japan for a month,

01:25:09.030 --> 01:25:10.560
and check out the scene there,

01:25:10.560 --> 01:25:12.560
and then come back,
and get busy.

01:25:12.560 --> 01:25:13.860
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Nice.

01:25:13.860 --> 01:25:16.510
Well, do you, early on,
you were collaborating --

01:25:16.510 --> 01:25:19.080
Pekar, Harvey Pekar
and other people could.

01:25:19.080 --> 01:25:22.190
But now, you, you know, you
have the creative control

01:25:22.190 --> 01:25:24.410
to do your own thing,
could you see a situation

01:25:24.410 --> 01:25:26.090
where you were collaborating
again, where you're turning

01:25:26.090 --> 01:25:27.390
over part of it to someone else?

01:25:27.390 --> 01:25:28.700
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: There are 3
people who I would work with,

01:25:28.700 --> 01:25:30.390
like off the top of the bat.

01:25:30.390 --> 01:25:33.020
Like, and they're the top
dogs as far as I'm concerned.

01:25:33.020 --> 01:25:34.320
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And
you can tweet this.

01:25:34.320 --> 01:25:35.730
And within an hour, maybe
they'll respond to you.

01:25:35.730 --> 01:25:37.030
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah, maybe.

01:25:37.030 --> 01:25:38.330
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah.

01:25:38.330 --> 01:25:41.110
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Alan Moore,
Frank Miller, Neil Gaiman.

01:25:41.110 --> 01:25:43.510
Like, I would collaborate
with those guys.

01:25:43.510 --> 01:25:46.050
And then, whatever
they had in mind.

01:25:46.050 --> 01:25:48.080
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Alan Moore,
Neil Gaiman, Frank Miller.

01:25:48.080 --> 01:25:49.380
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Frank
Miller, yeah.

01:25:49.380 --> 01:25:50.680
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: I've
talked to 2 of those 3.

01:25:50.680 --> 01:25:53.620
They're great interviewers,
great fun.

01:25:53.620 --> 01:25:55.600
Alan Moore, maybe
1 day, you know.

01:25:55.600 --> 01:25:56.900
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Oh, sure.

01:25:56.900 --> 01:25:58.930
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: We know Harvey
Pekar's widow, Joyce Brabner,

01:25:58.930 --> 01:26:02.970
knows Alan Moore, so there
may be a way for you.

01:26:02.970 --> 01:26:04.270
Yeah.

01:26:04.270 --> 01:26:05.570
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Oh, yeah.

01:26:05.570 --> 01:26:06.870
I'm not worried.

01:26:06.870 --> 01:26:08.170
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah, yeah.

01:26:08.170 --> 01:26:09.540
But, you know, so, and by the
way, I always, I've asked this

01:26:09.540 --> 01:26:11.830
of a lot of creators
because if you're any,

01:26:11.830 --> 01:26:14.490
a fan of any particular
kind of mind, often,

01:26:14.490 --> 01:26:17.990
you listen to that music to
fire you up, get you inspired.

01:26:17.990 --> 01:26:19.960
Did you listen to hip-hop while,

01:26:19.960 --> 01:26:22.330
did you have it banging while
you were creating Hip Hop

01:26:22.330 --> 01:26:23.630
Family Tree?

01:26:23.630 --> 01:26:26.290
And what do you listen
to when creating X-Men,

01:26:26.290 --> 01:26:27.590
your version of X-Men?

01:26:27.590 --> 01:26:28.890
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I did
listen to a lot

01:26:28.890 --> 01:26:31.310
of rap music while putting
Hip Hop Family Tree together.

01:26:31.310 --> 01:26:36.010
With X-Men, I consider it to
be kind of like a true epic,

01:26:36.010 --> 01:26:37.790
so this is how I
discovered, you know,

01:26:37.790 --> 01:26:40.960
the Game of Thrones
audiobooks and stuff like that.

01:26:40.960 --> 01:26:43.230
But just a lot of podcasts.

01:26:43.230 --> 01:26:44.900
Just a lot of fiction.

01:26:44.900 --> 01:26:48.370
A lot of, you know, of going
through Stephen King's body

01:26:48.370 --> 01:26:52.050
of work while I'm working, the,
you know, audiobooks because I,

01:26:52.050 --> 01:26:55.270
if I'm awake, I'm putting
that pencil to paper.

01:26:55.270 --> 01:26:58.750
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: Yeah,
and that gets you going.

01:26:58.750 --> 01:27:04.550
You know, I think the -- 1
last question for you is,

01:27:04.550 --> 01:27:06.490
do you remember -- many

01:27:06.490 --> 01:27:10.520
of us remember the first time
we saw something on a page

01:27:10.520 --> 01:27:13.770
that awakened us to the
miracle of what could be created

01:27:13.770 --> 01:27:16.060
on a page, whether
written, drawn.

01:27:16.060 --> 01:27:18.840
Do you remember what sort of,
what was that thing for you?

01:27:18.840 --> 01:27:21.020
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: I do, and it
wasn't a particular drawing,

01:27:21.020 --> 01:27:22.320
or words, or anything.

01:27:22.320 --> 01:27:25.530
It was the credits box
on an old X-Men comic

01:27:25.530 --> 01:27:28.490
with the name Chris
Claremont, writer.

01:27:28.490 --> 01:27:30.620
Dave Cochran, penciler.

01:27:30.620 --> 01:27:32.970
You know, Joseph
Rubenstein, inker.

01:27:32.970 --> 01:27:36.640
And this is before I even
knew how to read words,

01:27:36.640 --> 01:27:38.550
and I asked my mom,
what is this?

01:27:38.550 --> 01:27:40.370
And she says, okay,
this is a credit box.

01:27:40.370 --> 01:27:41.730
These are the people
who made the comic.

01:27:41.730 --> 01:27:43.300
And I thought, oh,
people make this.

01:27:43.300 --> 01:27:45.630
A human hand makes this comic.

01:27:45.630 --> 01:27:47.120
That's what I'm going
to do when I grow up.

01:27:47.120 --> 01:27:48.420
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: And
that raised the curtain

01:27:48.420 --> 01:27:49.720
on what you were doing.

01:27:49.720 --> 01:27:51.490
With that, we will close
the curtain here on--

01:27:51.490 --> 01:27:52.790
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Thank you, guys.

01:27:52.790 --> 01:27:54.510
&gt;&gt; Michael Cavna: With Eddie
P., the great Eddie P.,

01:27:54.510 --> 01:27:58.690
the Eisner-winning
Eddie P. Thank you.

